<h3>Data Flow Theory: Mouse Click to CPU</h3>
<div style="background-color: #e0e0e0; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
    
    <h4>The Complete Journey of a Mouse Click</h4>
    <div style="background-color: #f1f1f1; padding: 15px; border-radius: 5px; margin: 10px 0;">
        <pre style="white-space: pre-wrap; line-height: 1.5;">
<b>STEP 1: Physical Action</b>
1. User presses left mouse button
2. Mechanical switch closes circuit inside mouse
3. Mouse microcontroller detects voltage change

<b>STEP 2: Data Encoding</b>
4. Mouse encodes: "Button 1 pressed at coordinates (X,Y)"
5. Data packet created: [Header][Button State][Î”X][Î”Y][Checksum]
6. Packet sent via USB protocol

<b>STEP 3: USB Transmission</b>
7. USB data travels through cable (D+ and D- wires)
8. USB controller on motherboard receives packet
9. Controller interrupts CPU: "Hey, I have data!"

<b>STEP 4: System Processing</b>
10. CPU pauses current task (context switch)
11. Reads mouse data from USB controller's buffer
12. Updates mouse cursor position in RAM
13. Notifies operating system: "Mouse event occurred"

<b>STEP 5: Application Response</b>
14. OS checks which window has focus
15. Sends mouse click event to application
16. Application processes click (e.g., opens file)
17. Results displayed on screen via GPU
        </pre>
    </div>
    
