<h3>Detailed Boot Process Mapping</h3>
<div style="background-color: #e0e0e0; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
    
    <h4>The Complete Boot Journey: From Power to Desktop</h4>
    <div style="background-color: #fff; padding: 15px; border-radius: 5px; margin: 10px 0;">
        <pre style="background-color: #f9f9f9; padding: 15px; border-radius: 5px; font-family: monospace; line-height: 1.4;">
<b>PHASE 1: POWER-ON (POST) - 0 to 2 seconds</b>
[Power Button] â†’ PSU receives signal â†’ All voltage rails stabilize
â†“
PSU sends "Power Good" signal to motherboard
â†“
CPU reset pin released â†’ CPU begins executing from hardwired address (FFFFFFF0h)
â†“
CPU loads BIOS/UEFI from flash chip â†’ POST begins
    â”œâ”€â”€ CPU test
    â”œâ”€â”€ RAM test (beep codes if failed)
    â”œâ”€â”€ GPU initialization
    â”œâ”€â”€ Storage device detection
    â””â”€â”€ Peripheral enumeration

<b>PHASE 2: BOOTLOADER - 2 to 5 seconds</b>
BIOS reads boot order from CMOS/NVRAM
â†“
BIOS loads first sector (512 bytes) from boot device â†’ MBR/GPT
â†“
Bootloader (GRUB, Windows Boot Manager) takes control
â†“
Bootloader loads kernel into RAM
â†“
Control transferred to operating system kernel

<b>PHASE 3: KERNEL INITIALIZATION - 5 to 15 seconds</b>
Kernel initializes:
    â”œâ”€â”€ Memory management
    â”œâ”€â”€ Process scheduler
    â”œâ”€â”€ Device drivers
    â”œâ”€â”€ File systems
    â””â”€â”€ Network stack
â†“
Kernel starts init process (PID 1) â†’ systemd (Linux) or smss.exe (Windows)
â†“
User space initialization begins

<b>PHASE 4: USER SPACE - 15 to 30 seconds</b>
Startup services launch:
    â”œâ”€â”€ Login manager (Display Manager/GINA)
    â”œâ”€â”€ Desktop environment
    â”œâ”€â”€ Background services
    â””â”€â”€ User applications (startup folder)
â†“
Desktop ready for user interaction
        </pre>
    </div>
    
    <h4>Boot Time Optimization Analysis</h4>
    <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 20px; margin-top: 15px;">
