<h3>Q&A Session: Week 1 Review</h3>
<div style="background-color: #e0e0e0; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
    
    <h4>Common Questions & Detailed Answers</h4>
    
    <div style="background-color: #fff; padding: 15px; border-radius: 5px; margin: 10px 0;">
        <details>
            <summary><b>Q1: Why does my computer beep when starting?</b></summary>
            <div style="margin-top: 10px; padding: 10px; background: #f9f9f9; border-radius: 3px;">
                <p><b>A:</b> Those are POST (Power-On Self-Test) beep codes. Different patterns mean different things:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><b>1 short beep:</b> Normal POST - system OK</li>
                    <li><b>1 long, 2 short:</b> Video card error</li>
                    <li><b>Continuous short beeps:</b> Power supply or motherboard issue</li>
                    <li><b>1 long, 3 short:</b> Memory (RAM) error</li>
                    <li><b>No beep:</b> Power supply, motherboard, or speaker issue</li>
                </ul>
                <p><b>Check:</b> Your motherboard manual has the specific beep codes for your model.</p>
            </div>
        </details>
        
        <details style="margin-top: 10px;">
            <summary><b>Q2: How much thermal paste should I use?</b></summary>
            <div style="margin-top: 10px; padding: 10px; background: #f9f9f9; border-radius: 3px;">
                <p><b>A:</b> For most modern CPUs (Intel LGA1700/AMD AM4/AM5):</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><b>Pea-sized method:</b> Rice grain or small pea in center (most common)</li>
                    <li><b>X method:</b> Draw an X across the IHS (for larger CPUs)</li>
                    <li><b>Spread method:</b> Spread thin, even layer (requires care)</li>
                </ul>
                <p><b>Key points:</b></p>
                <ol>
                    <li>Less is more - excess can cause poor contact or spill onto socket</li>
                    <li>Cover should be about the thickness of a piece of paper</li>
                    <li>If it squeezes out edges, you used too much</li>
                    <li>Non-conductive paste is safer for beginners</li>
                </ol>
            </div>
        </details>
        
        <details style="margin-top: 10px;">
            <summary><b>Q3: Can I mix RAM of different speeds?</b></summary>
            <div style="margin-top: 10px; padding: 10px; background: #f9f9f9; border-radius: 3px;">
                <p><b>A:</b> Technically yes, but with significant limitations:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><b>All RAM will run at slowest speed</b> of any installed module</li>
                    <li><b>Timings will use most conservative</b> (slowest) settings</li>
                    <li><b>Dual-channel may not work</b> with mismatched capacities</li>
                    <li><b>Stability issues</b> are common with mixed RAM</li>
                </ul>
                <p><b>Best practice:</b> Use identical kits (same brand, model, speed, timings). If you must mix:</p>
                <ol>
                    <li>Try to match speed and timings manually in BIOS</li>
                    <li>Run MemTest86 for several hours to check stability</li>
                    <li>Be prepared for system crashes or reduced performance</li>
                </ol>
            </div>
        </details>
        
        <details style="margin-top: 10px;">
            <summary><b>Q4: How do I know if my PSU is failing?</b></summary>
            <div style="margin-top: 10px; padding: 10px; background: #f9f9f9; border-radius: 3px;">
                <p><b>A:</b> Watch for these warning signs:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><b>Random shutdowns/restarts</b> under load</li>
                    <li><b>Burning smell</b> from the PSU vents</li>
                    <li><b>Loud coil whine</b> or fan noise</li>
                    <li><b>Blue screen errors</b> mentioning power</li>
                    <li><b>Peripheral failures</b> (USB devices disconnecting)</li>
                    <li><b>Visual signs:</b> Bulging capacitors, burn marks</li>
                </ul>
                <p><b>Testing:</b></p>
                <ol>
                    <li>Use a PSU tester ($15-30) to check voltages</li>
                    <li>+12V should be 11.4V-12.6V</li>
                    <li>+5V should be 4.75V-5.25V</li>
                    <li>+3.3V should be 3.14V-3.47V</li>
                    <li>Replace if voltages are outside these ranges</li>
                </ol>
            </div>
        </details>
        
        <details style="margin-top: 10px;">
            <summary><b>Q5: What's the difference between BIOS and UEFI?</b></summary>
            <div style="margin-top: 10px; padding: 10px; background: #f9f9f9; border-radius: 3px;">
                <p><b>A:</b> Major differences:</p>
                <table style="width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 10px 0;">
                    <tr style="background: #4A90E2; color: white;">
                        <th style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Feature</th>
                        <th style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">BIOS (Legacy)</th>
                        <th style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">UEFI (Modern)</th>
                    </tr>
                    <tr style="background: #f8f9fa;">
                        <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Interface</td>
                        <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Text-only, keyboard navigation</td>
                        <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Graphical, mouse support</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr style="background: white;">
                        <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Disk Support</td>
                        <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">MBR only, max 2TB</td>
                        <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">GPT, drives over 2TB</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr style="background: #f8f9fa;">
                        <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Boot Speed</td>
                        <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Slower</td>
                        <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Faster (Fast Boot)</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr style="background: white;">
                        <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Security</td>
                        <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Basic</td>
                        <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Secure Boot, TPM support</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr style="background: #f8f9fa;">
                        <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Drivers</td>
                        <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Built-in only</td>
                        <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Can load from disk</td>
                    </tr>
                </table>
                <p><b>Modern systems:</b> Most use UEFI with "CSM" (Compatibility Support Module) for backward compatibility.</p>
            </div>
        </details>
    </div>
    
    <h4>Submit Your Questions</h4>
    <div style="background-color: #fff3cd; padding: 15px; border-radius: 5px; margin: 10px 0;">
        <p><b>Still have questions? Submit them here:</b></p>
        <textarea placeholder="Type your question about Week 1 topics here..." style="width: 100%; height: 100px; padding: 10px; border-radius: 5px; border: 1px solid #ccc; margin-bottom: 10px;"></textarea>
        <button style="background: #4A90E2; color: white; border: none; padding: 10px 20px; border-radius: 5px; cursor: pointer;">Submit Question</button>
    </div>
</div>

