    <h4>Hybrid Kernels (Windows NT, macOS)</h4>
    <div style="background-color: #f1f1f1; padding: 15px; border-radius: 5px; margin: 10px 0;">
        <p><b>Best of Both Worlds:</b> Hybrid kernels combine aspects of both monolithic and microkernel designs.</p>
        
        <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 20px; margin-top: 10px;">
            <div>
                <h5>Windows NT Kernel Design</h5>
                <ul>
                    <li><b>Executive Services:</b> Runs in kernel mode</li>
                    <li><b>User Mode:</b> Subsystem for Win32, POSIX, etc.</li>
                    <li><b>Hardware Abstraction Layer (HAL):</b> Isolates hardware specifics</li>
                    <li><b>Microkernel:</b> Handles thread scheduling, interrupts</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            
            <div>
                <h5>macOS (XNU Kernel)</h5>
                <ul>
                    <li><b>Mach Microkernel:</b> Core messaging, memory management</li>
                    <li><b>BSD Layer:</b> Unix compatibility, file system, network</li>
                    <li><b>I/O Kit:</b> Device driver framework</li>
                    <li><b>Apple-specific:</b> Security, graphics, etc.</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</div>

