<h3>Key Learning Points:</h3>
<ol>
    <li><b>Partition Tables:</b> Understanding MBR limitations vs GPT advantages</li>
    <li><b>File Systems:</b> Choosing appropriate FS for different use cases</li>
    <li><b>Partitioning Strategies:</b> Different approaches for different needs</li>
    <li><b>Linux Partition Hierarchy:</b> Purpose of /, /home, /boot, /var, etc.</li>
    <li><b>Windows Partition Layout:</b> Recovery, EFI, MSR, and main partitions</li>
    <li><b>Practical Skills:</b> Using partitioning tools and analyzing existing layouts</li>
</ol>

<div style="background-color: #e8f5e8; padding: 15px; margin: 20px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
    <h3>ğŸ’¡ Partitioning Best Practices:</h3>
    <ul>
        <li><b>Always Backup First:</b> Partitioning can (and will) destroy data</li>
        <li><b>Use GPT for Modern Systems:</b> Unless you need legacy BIOS compatibility</li>
        <li><b>Separate OS and Data:</b> Keep /home or Documents on separate partition</li>
        <li><b>Align Partitions:</b> Modern SSDs need 4K/1MB alignment for performance</li>
        <li><b>Leave Unallocated Space:</b> 10-20% free for wear leveling (SSDs) and future needs</li>
        <li><b>Consider Future Growth:</b> Don't allocate 100% of disk immediately</li>
        <li><b>Document Your Layout:</b> Take screenshots before making changes</li>
        <li><b>Test in VM First:</b> Practice partitioning schemes virtually before real hardware</li>
        <li><b>Understand Your Workload:</b> Different uses need different partitioning</li>
        <li><b>Keep It Simple:</b> More partitions = more complexity = more potential issues</li>
    </ul>
</div>

