<h3>Key Learning Points:</h3>
<ol>
    <li><b>CLI vs GUI:</b> Understanding when to use command line vs graphical interface</li>
    <li><b>Basic Navigation:</b> Moving through filesystems with cd, ls/dir, pwd</li>
    <li><b>File Operations:</b> Creating and managing directories with mkdir, rmdir</li>
    <li><b>System Information:</b> Gathering system data with systeminfo, uname, etc.</li>
    <li><b>Path Notation:</b> Understanding ., .., ~, /, \ and wildcards</li>
    <li><b>Command Syntax:</b> Learning command structure and common options/flags</li>
    <li><b>Practical Application:</b> Using CLI for real system administration tasks</li>
</ol>

<div style="background-color: #e8f5e8; padding: 15px; margin: 20px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
    <h3>ğŸ’¡ CLI Best Practices:</h3>
    <ul>
        <li><b>Use Tab Completion:</b> Saves typing and prevents errors</li>
        <li><b>Read Manual Pages:</b> man [command] or [command] --help</li>
        <li><b>Test Dangerous Commands First:</b> Use echo or dry-run options</li>
        <li><b>Use History:</b> Up arrow to recall previous commands</li>
        <li><b>Document Your Commands:</b> Keep a log of useful commands</li>
        <li><b>Understand Before Running:</b> Don't copy-paste commands you don't understand</li>
        <li><b>Use Absolute Paths for Scripts:</b> Relative paths can break</li>
        <li><b>Check Your Current Directory:</b> pwd or echo %CD% before destructive operations</li>
        <li><b>Quote Paths with Spaces:</b> Always use quotes for paths containing spaces</li>
        <li><b>Learn Output Redirection:</b> > to save output, >> to append</li>
    </ul>
</div>

