<h3>Detailed File Operation Examples</h3>
<div style="background-color: #e0e0e0; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
    
    <h4>Creating and Viewing Files</h4>
    <div style="background-color: #fff; padding: 15px; border-radius: 5px; margin: 10px 0;">
        <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 20px;">
            <div>
                <h5>Windows File Operations</h5>
                <pre style="background-color: #0C0C0C; color: #CCCCCC; padding: 10px; border-radius: 5px;">
# Create empty file
echo.>file.txt
copy nul empty.txt
type nul > file.txt

# Create file with content
echo Hello World > hello.txt
echo Second line >> hello.txt

# View files
type hello.txt
more hello.txt          # Page through
find "World" hello.txt  # Search in file

# Copy files
copy hello.txt hello_backup.txt
copy *.txt backups\     # Copy all txt files
copy /v hello.txt copy.txt  # Verify copy

# Move/rename
move hello.txt documents\
ren old.txt new.txt

# Delete
del file.txt
del *.tmp              # Delete all tmp files
del /f read_only.txt   # Force delete
del /s *.bak           # Delete in subfolders

# Compare files
fc file1.txt file2.txt
fc /b binary1.bin binary2.bin

# File information
dir hello.txt
for %i in (hello.txt) do @echo %~zi bytes
                </pre>
            </div>
            
            <div>
                <h5>Linux/macOS File Operations</h5>
                <pre style="background-color: #300A24; color: #00FF00; padding: 10px; border-radius: 5px;">
# Create empty file
touch file.txt
> empty.txt            # Redirection method

# Create file with content
echo "Hello World" > hello.txt
echo "Second line" >> hello.txt
cat > newfile.txt     # Type content, Ctrl+D to save

# View files
cat hello.txt
less hello.txt        # Better for large files
head -5 hello.txt     # First 5 lines
tail -5 hello.txt     # Last 5 lines
tail -f log.txt       # Follow (watch growing file)

# Copy files
cp hello.txt hello_backup.txt
cp -r dir1 dir2       # Recursive copy
cp -i source dest     # Interactive (prompt)
cp -v file.txt backup # Verbose (show progress)

# Move/rename
mv hello.txt documents/
mv oldname newname
mv -i file.txt dest   # Prompt before overwrite

# Delete
rm file.txt
rm -i file.txt        # Interactive (prompt)
rm -f file.txt        # Force (no prompt)
rm -r directory       # Recursive delete
rm -rf dir           # DANGEROUS: force recursive

# Compare files
diff file1.txt file2.txt
diff -u file1 file2   # Unified diff format
diff -y file1 file2   # Side-by-side comparison

# File information
stat hello.txt        # Detailed stats
file hello.txt        # File type detection
wc hello.txt          # Word count (lines, words, chars)
                </pre>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
    
    <h4>Wildcards and Pattern Matching</h4>
    <div style="background-color: #fff3cd; padding: 15px; border-radius: 5px; margin: 10px 0;">
        <h5>Powerful Pattern Matching Examples</h5>
        
        <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 20px; margin-top: 10px;">
            <div>
                <h6>Basic Wildcards</h6>
                <pre style="background-color: #f1f1f1; padding: 10px; border-radius: 5px;">
*       Matches any characters
?       Matches any single character
[abc]   Matches a, b, or c
[a-z]   Matches any lowercase letter
[0-9]   Matches any digit
[!abc]  Matches anything except a, b, c

Examples:
*.txt           All .txt files
image*.jpg      Files starting with "image" ending .jpg
file?.txt       file1.txt, fileA.txt, etc.
report[0-9].txt report0.txt through report9.txt
data[!0-9].csv  dataA.csv, dataB.csv (not data1.csv)
                </pre>
            </div>
            
            <div>
                <h6>Advanced Pattern Matching (Linux/Bash)</h6>
                <pre style="background-color: #f1f1f1; padding: 10px; border-radius: 5px;">
{pattern1,pattern2}  Matches either pattern
{1..10}              Range: 1, 2, 3, ..., 10
{a..z}               Letters a through z
{01..10}             Zero-padded: 01, 02, ..., 10

Examples:
cp file.{txt,bak}    Copy file.txt to file.bak
touch file{1..5}.txt Create file1.txt through file5.txt
mkdir {jan,feb,mar}_2023
ls *.{jpg,png,gif}   All image files
rm -f *.{log,tmp}    Delete all log and tmp files

# Brace expansion combinations
echo {A,B}{1,2}      # A1 A2 B1 B2
mkdir -p src/{main,test}/{java,resources}
                </pre>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</div>

<h3>File Permissions & Ownership</h3>
