<h3>Key Learning Points:</h3>
<ol>
    <li><b>File Operations:</b> Mastery of create, copy, move, delete operations</li>
    <li><b>Permission Systems:</b> Understanding Linux (rwx) and Windows (NTFS) permissions</li>
    <li><b>Permission Management:</b> Using chmod, chown, icacls effectively</li>
    <li><b>File Searching:</b> Finding files by name, content, size, and other attributes</li>
    <li><b>Text Processing:</b> Manipulating file content with grep, sed, awk, etc.</li>
    <li><b>Wildcard Patterns:</b> Using *, ?, [], {} for efficient file operations</li>
    <li><b>Security Principles:</b> Applying least privilege to file permissions</li>
</ol>

<div style="background-color: #e8f5e8; padding: 15px; margin: 20px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
    <h3>ğŸ’¡ File Management Best Practices:</h3>
    <ul>
        <li><b>Backup Before Bulk Operations:</b> Especially before recursive deletes</li>
        <li><b>Use -i (interactive) Flag:</b> When learning or with dangerous operations</li>
        <li><b>Test with echo First:</b> For complex find/delete operations: find ... -exec echo rm {} \;</li>
        <li><b>Understand Recursive Flags:</b> -R or /s affects everything in directory tree</li>
        <li><b>Quote Paths with Spaces:</b> Always use "quotes" for paths containing spaces</li>
        <li><b>Use Tab Completion:</b> Prevents typos in file/directory names</li>
        <li><b>Check Current Directory:</b> pwd or echo %CD% before destructive operations</li>
        <li><b>Document Permission Changes:</b> Keep log of why permissions were modified</li>
        <li><b>Apply Principle of Least Privilege:</b> Give minimum necessary permissions</li>
        <li><b>Regular Permission Audits:</b> Periodically review critical file permissions</li>
    </ul>
</div>

