<h3>Key Learning Points:</h3>
<ol>
    <li><b>Advanced Navigation:</b> Mastery of pushd/popd, CDPATH, and directory stacks</li>
    <li><b>Environment Variables:</b> Understanding, setting, and using environment variables</li>
    <li><b>Shell Scripting Basics:</b> Creating executable scripts with proper shebang</li>
    <li><b>Variables in Scripts:</b> Declaration, assignment, and manipulation</li>
    <li><b>Conditional Logic:</b> if/then/else statements for decision making</li>
    <li><b>Loop Structures:</b> for, while, until loops for repetition</li>
    <li><b>User Input:</b> Reading and processing user input in scripts</li>
    <li><b>Script Organization:</b> Creating modular, maintainable scripts</li>
</ol>

<div style="background-color: #e8f5e8; padding: 15px; margin: 20px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
    <h3>ğŸ’¡ Scripting Best Practices:</h3>
    <ul>
        <li><b>Start Simple:</b> Make it work, then make it better, then make it fast</li>
        <li><b>Add Error Handling Early:</b> Check for failures and exit gracefully</li>
        <li><b>Use Meaningful Variable Names:</b> total_files vs tf</li>
        <li><b>Comment Your Code:</b> Explain why, not what (code should be self-documenting)</li>
        <li><b>Test Incrementally:</b> Test each part as you write it</li>
        <li><b>Use Functions:</b> Break complex scripts into reusable functions</li>
        <li><b>Validate Input:</b> Never trust user input or external data</li>
        <li><b>Enable Debug Mode:</b> set -x in bash or remove @echo off in batch</li>
        <li><b>Check Exit Codes:</b> $? in bash, %ERRORLEVEL% in batch</li>
        <li><b>Keep It Portable:</b> Avoid shell-specific features when possible</li>
        <li><b>Document Your Scripts:</b> Include usage, examples, and requirements</li>
        <li><b>Version Control:</b> Use git even for small scripts</li>
    </ul>
</div>

