            </div>

            <div style="background: #fff0f0; padding: 15px; border-radius: 5px;">
                <h4>ğŸ¯ Mnemonic to Remember Layers</h4>
                <p><b>A</b>ll <b>P</b>eople <b>S</b>eem <b>T</b>o <b>N</b>eed <b>D</b>ata <b>P</b>rocessing</p>
                <p>or</p>
                <p><b>P</b>lease <b>D</b>o <b>N</b>ot <b>T</b>hrow <b>S</b>ausage <b>P</b>izza <b>A</b>way</p>

                <div style="margin-top: 15px; padding: 10px; background: #ffe6e6; border-radius: 5px;">
                    <h5>Layer Functions Simplified:</h5>
                    <ul style="margin: 0; padding-left: 20px;">
                        <li><b>Layer 7:</b> What user sees (Browser, Email)</li>
                        <li><b>Layer 6:</b> Translation & Encryption</li>
                        <li><b>Layer 5:</b> Session Management</li>
                        <li><b>Layer 4:</b> Reliable Delivery (TCP/UDP)</li>
                        <li><b>Layer 3:</b> Routing & Addressing (IP)</li>
                        <li><b>Layer 2:</b> Local Network Delivery</li>
                        <li><b>Layer 1:</b> Physical Connection</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <h3>Data Flow Through OSI Layers</h3>
        <div style="background-color: #e0e0e0; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
            <h4>ğŸ“¨ Example: Sending an Email</h4>

            <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 20px; margin-top: 15px;">
                <div>
                    <h5>Sender's Computer (Encapsulation)</h5>
                    <pre style="background: white; padding: 10px; border-radius: 5px;">
    1. Application (Layer 7):
    User types: "Hello" in email
    â†’ Becomes SMTP protocol data

    2. Presentation (Layer 6):
    Data encrypted (SSL/TLS)
    â†’ Encrypted SMTP data

    3. Session (Layer 5):
    Establishes session with mail server
    â†’ Session ID added

    4. Transport (Layer 4):
    TCP segments data, adds port numbers
    â†’ TCP segments with source/dest ports

    5. Network (Layer 3):
    IP adds source/destination addresses
    â†’ IP packets with 192.168.1.10 â†’ 74.125.24.109

    6. Data Link (Layer 2):
    Ethernet adds MAC addresses
    â†’ Ethernet frames with MAC addresses

    7. Physical (Layer 1):
    Converts to electrical signals
    â†’ Electrical pulses on wire
                </pre>
                </div>

                <div>
                    <h5>Receiver's Computer (Decapsulation)</h5>
                    <pre style="background: white; padding: 10px; border-radius: 5px;">
    1. Physical (Layer 1):
    Receives electrical signals
    â†’ Converts to binary data

    2. Data Link (Layer 2):
    Checks MAC address, removes frame header
    â†’ Extracts IP packet

    3. Network (Layer 3):
    Checks IP address, routes if needed
    â†’ Extracts TCP segment

    4. Transport (Layer 4):
    TCP reassembles segments, checks order
    â†’ Extracts application data

    5. Session (Layer 5):
    Manages session, keeps connection alive
    â†’ Passes to presentation layer

    6. Presentation (Layer 6):
    Decrypts data, translates if needed
    â†’ Decrypted SMTP data

    7. Application (Layer 7):
    Email client displays "Hello"
    â†’ User reads message
                </pre>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <h3>Practical Network Commands</h3>
        <div style="background-color: #f0f8ff; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
            <h4>ğŸ”§ Hands-On: Basic Network Diagnostics</h4>

            <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 20px;">
                <div>
                    <h5>Windows Commands</h5>
                    <pre style="background: #36454f; color: white; padding: 10px; border-radius: 5px;">
