    <h3>Common IP Issues & Solutions</h3>
    <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 20px; margin: 20px 0;">
        <div style="background: #e8f5e8; padding: 15px; border-radius: 5px;">
            <h4>ğŸ”´ Issue 1: APIPA Address (169.254.x.x)</h4>

            <div style="background: white; padding: 15px; border-radius: 5px; margin-top: 10px;">
                <h5>Symptoms:</h5>
                <ul>
                    <li>IP address starts with 169.254</li>
                    <li>"Limited connectivity" message</li>
                    <li>Can't access network resources</li>
                    <li>No internet access</li>
                </ul>

                <h5 style="margin-top: 15px;">Causes:</h5>
                <ol>
                    <li>DHCP server unavailable</li>
                    <li>Network cable disconnected</li>
                    <li>DHCP scope exhausted</li>
                    <li>Firewall blocking DHCP</li>
                    <li>VLAN misconfiguration</li>
                </ol>

                <div style="margin-top: 15px; padding: 10px; background: #d4edda; border-radius: 5px;">
                    <h6>Solutions:</h6>
                    <pre style="background: white; padding: 10px; border-radius: 5px;">
# Windows
ipconfig /release
ipconfig /renew
ipconfig /all

# Check DHCP server
netsh interface ipv4 show dhcp

# Linux
sudo dhclient -r
sudo dhclient

# Check DHCP leases
cat /var/lib/dhcp/dhclient.leases
                </pre>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div style="background: #ffe6e6; padding: 15px; border-radius: 5px;">
            <h4>ğŸ”´ Issue 2: IP Address Conflict</h4>

            <div style="background: white; padding: 15px; border-radius: 5px; margin-top: 10px;">
                <h5>Symptoms:</h5>
                <ul>
                    <li>"IP address conflict" popup</li>
                    <li>Intermittent connectivity</li>
                    <li>Network drops randomly</li>
                    <li>Some services work, others don't</li>
                </ul>

                <h5 style="margin-top: 15px;">Causes:</h1>
                    <ol>
                        <li>Manual IP same as DHCP assigned</li>
                        <li>Duplicate static IP assignments</li>
                        <li>Rogue DHCP server</li>
                        <li>Device with reserved IP turned on</li>
                    </ol>

                    <div style="margin-top: 15px; padding: 10px; background: #f8d7da; border-radius: 5px;">
                        <h6>Solutions:</h6>
                        <pre style="background: white; padding: 10px; border-radius: 5px;">
# Find conflicting IP
arp -a

# Release and renew
ipconfig /release
ipconfig /renew

# Find device with duplicate IP
ping 192.168.1.100
arp -a 192.168.1.100

# Check DHCP reservations
# Use DHCP management console
                </pre>
                    </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 20px; margin: 20px 0;">
        <div style="background: #fff3cd; padding: 15px; border-radius: 5px;">
            <h4>ğŸ”´ Issue 3: Wrong Subnet Mask</h4>

            <div style="background: white; padding: 15px; border-radius: 5px; margin-top: 10px;">
                <h5>Symptoms:</h5>
                <ul>
                    <li>Can ping some devices, not others</li>
                    <li>Local network works, remote fails</li>
                    <li>Intermittent connectivity issues</li>
                    <li>ARP entries missing</li>
                </ul>

                <h5 style="margin-top: 15px;">Causes:</h5>
                <ol>
                    <li>Manual configuration error</li>
                    <li>DHCP providing wrong mask</li>
                    <li>VLSM misconfiguration</li>
                    <li>Network redesign not propagated</li>
                </ol>

                <div style="margin-top: 15px; padding: 10px; background: #fff8e1; border-radius: 5px;">
                    <h6>Solutions:</h6>
                    <pre style="background: white; padding: 10px; border-radius: 5px;">
# Check current configuration
ipconfig /all
ifconfig

# Verify subnet calculations
# IP: 192.168.1.100, Mask: 255.255.255.0
# Network: 192.168.1.0
# Broadcast: 192.168.1.255
# Valid hosts: 192.168.1.1 - 192.168.1.254

# Compare with other devices
# All devices in same subnet must have same mask
                </pre>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div style="background: #e3f2fd; padding: 15px; border-radius: 5px;">
            <h4>ğŸ”´ Issue 4: Default Gateway Problems</h4>

            <div style="background: white; padding: 15px; border-radius: 5px; margin-top: 10px;">
                <h5>Symptoms:</h5>
                <ul>
                    <li>Local network access works</li>
                    <li>No internet access</li>
                    <li>Can't reach other subnets</li>
                    <li>Can ping gateway but not beyond</li>
                </ul>

                <h5 style="margin-top: 15px;">Causes:</h5>
                <ol>
                    <li>Wrong gateway IP configured</li>
                    <li>Gateway device down</li>
                    <li>Gateway in different subnet</li>
                    <li>Routing issues on gateway</li>
                </ol>

                <div style="margin-top: 15px; padding: 10px; background: #bbdefb; border-radius: 5px;">
                    <h6>Solutions:</h6>
                    <pre style="background: white; padding: 10px; border-radius: 5px;">
# Check gateway configuration
ipconfig /all
route print

# Test gateway connectivity
ping 192.168.1.1
tracert 8.8.8.8

# Verify gateway is in same subnet
# IP: 192.168.1.100/24
# Gateway must be 192.168.1.x

# Check gateway device
# Is it powered on? Correctly configured?
                </pre>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

