    <h3>Troubleshooting Scenarios</h3>
    <div style="background-color: #f0f8ff; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
        <h4>ğŸ” Real-World Case Studies</h4>

        <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 20px; margin-top: 15px;">
            <div style="background: white; padding: 15px; border-radius: 5px;">
                <h5>Scenario 1: The Intermittent Office</h5>
                <p><b>Situation:</b> Office users report random network drops. Sometimes internet works, sometimes it doesn't.</p>

                <div style="margin-top: 10px; padding: 10px; background: #e3f2fd; border-radius: 5px;">
                    <h6>Investigation:</h6>
                    <ol>
                        <li>Check event logs - find DHCP errors</li>
                        <li>Run ipconfig on affected machines - some have 169.254.x.x</li>
                        <li>Check DHCP server - scope is 90% utilized</li>
                        <li>Discover lease time is 8 days (too long)</li>
                        <li>Find many disconnected devices holding leases</li>
                    </ol>
                </div>

                <div style="margin-top: 10px; padding: 10px; background: #d4edda; border-radius: 5px;">
                    <h6>Solution:</h6>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Reduce DHCP lease time to 24 hours</li>
                        <li>Increase DHCP scope size</li>
                        <li>Add DHCP reservations for critical devices</li>
                        <li>Implement better IP address management</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div style="background: white; padding: 15px; border-radius: 5px;">
                <h5>Scenario 2: The Mysterious Printer</h5>
                <p><b>Situation:</b> Network printer works for some users but not others. Can print from some computers, not all.</p>

                <div style="margin-top: 10px; padding: 10px; background: #fff3cd; border-radius: 5px;">
                    <h6>Investigation:</h6>
                    <ol>
                        <li>Check printer IP: 192.168.1.50</li>
                        <li>Check subnet masks: Some computers have /24, others /23</li>
                        <li>Discover network was recently expanded</li>
                        <li>Some devices have old subnet mask (255.255.255.0)</li>
                        <li>New network range is 192.168.0.0/23 (192.168.0.1-192.168.1.254)</li>
                    </ol>
                </div>

                <div style="margin-top: 10px; padding: 10px; background: #f8d7da; border-radius: 5px;">
                    <h6>Solution:</h6>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Update DHCP to provide correct subnet mask (/23)</li>
                        <li>Manually update static devices</li>
                        <li>Communicate network changes to all users</li>
                        <li>Document new IP addressing scheme</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div style="margin-top: 20px;">
            <h5>Scenario 3: The New Branch Office</h5>
            <div style="background: white; padding: 15px; border-radius: 5px;">
                <p><b>Situation:</b> New office opened, but computers can't access main office resources. Local network works fine.</p>

                <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 20px; margin-top: 10px;">
                    <div>
                        <h6>Investigation:</h6>
                        <table style="width: 100%; font-size: 0.9em;">
                            <tr>
                                <td style="padding: 5px;">Branch IP range:</td>
                                <td style="padding: 5px;">10.20.0.0/24</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr style="background: #f8f9fa;">
                                <td style="padding: 5px;">Main office range:</td>
                                <td style="padding: 5px;">10.10.0.0/16</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td style="padding: 5px;">Gateway:</td>
                                <td style="padding: 5px;">10.20.0.1</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr style="background: #f8f9fa;">
                                <td style="padding: 5px;">VPN tunnel:</td>
                                <td style="padding: 5px;">Active and passing traffic</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td style="padding: 5px;">Traceroute:</td>
                                <td style="padding: 5px;">Stops at branch router</td>
                            </tr>
                        </table>
                    </div>

                    <div>
                        <h6>Problem Found:</h6>
                        <ul>
                            <li>Branch router missing route to main office</li>
                            <li>Static route not configured</li>
                            <li>Routing protocol not enabled</li>
                            <li>Main office router missing return route</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div style="margin-top: 15px; padding: 10px; background: #e8f5e8; border-radius: 5px;">
                    <h6>Solution:</h6>
                    <pre style="background: white; padding: 10px; border-radius: 5px;">
# On branch router
ip route 10.10.0.0 255.255.0.0 [VPN-interface]

# On main office router  
ip route 10.20.0.0 255.255.255.0 [VPN-interface]

# Or enable dynamic routing (OSPF, EIGRP)
                </pre>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

