        <div style="margin-top: 20px; padding: 15px; background: white; border-radius: 5px;">
            <h5>ğŸ“Š Quiz Answers & Explanations</h5>

            <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 20px;">
                <div>
                    <h6>Multiple Choice Answers:</h6>
                    <ol>
                        <li>B - 255.255.0.0 (Class B default)</li>
                        <li>B - 192.168.1.1 (Private range)</li>
                        <li>A - Automatic Private IP Addressing</li>
                        <li>A - 14 hosts (16 total - 2)</li>
                        <li>B - arp -a (shows ARP cache)</li>
                    </ol>
                </div>

                <div>
                    <h6>True/False Answers:</h6>
                    <ol start="6">
                        <li>True - DHCP uses UDP ports 67 (server) and 68 (client)</li>
                        <li>False - 127.0.0.1 is loopback (private)</li>
                        <li>False - /30 has 2 usable hosts (4 total - 2)</li>
                        <li>True - CIDR is Classless Inter-Domain Routing</li>
                        <li>True - VLSM = Variable Length Subnet Masking</li>
                    </ol>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div style="margin-top: 15px;">
                <h6>Practical Problem Solutions:</h6>
                <p><b>11. 192.168.1.130/27</b></p>
                <pre style="background: #f5f5f5; padding: 10px; border-radius: 5px;">
Mask: 255.255.255.224 (/27)
Magic number: 256 - 224 = 32
Network: 192.168.1.128 (130 Ã· 32 = 4, remainder 2, network = 4Ã—32 = 128)
Broadcast: 192.168.1.159 (128 + 32 - 1 = 159)
First host: 192.168.1.129
Last host: 192.168.1.158
Usable hosts: 30
            </pre>

                <p style="margin-top: 15px;"><b>12. Subnet Design:</b></p>
                <pre style="background: #f5f5f5; padding: 10px; border-radius: 5px;">
Dept 1 (60 hosts): 10.0.1.0/26 (62 hosts) - /26 = 64 - 2 = 62
Dept 2 (30 hosts): 10.0.1.64/27 (30 hosts) - /27 = 32 - 2 = 30  
Dept 3 (12 hosts): 10.0.1.96/28 (14 hosts) - /28 = 16 - 2 = 14
Dept 4 (6 hosts): 10.0.1.112/29 (6 hosts) - /29 = 8 - 2 = 6

VLSM allows efficient use of 10.0.0.0/16 space
