<h3>Advanced TraceRoute Techniques</h3>
<div style="background-color: #f0f8ff; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
    <h4>ğŸš€ Beyond Basic Tracing</h4>
    
    <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 20px; margin-top: 15px;">
        <div>
            <h5>Protocol Variations</h5>
            
            <div style="background: white; padding: 15px; border-radius: 5px;">
                <h6>Different Protocols for Different Situations:</h6>
                
                <div style="margin-bottom: 15px;">
                    <h6>ICMP TraceRoute (Windows default):</h6>
                    <pre style="background: #f5f5f5; padding: 10px; border-radius: 5px;">
# Windows (default)
tracert google.com

# Linux with ICMP
traceroute -I google.com

# Pros: Simple, works through most firewalls
# Cons: Often rate-limited or blocked
                    </pre>
                </div>
                
                <div style="margin-bottom: 15px;">
                    <h6>UDP TraceRoute (Linux default):</h6>
                    <pre style="background: #f5f5f5; padding: 10px; border-radius: 5px;">
# Linux (default)
traceroute google.com

# Starts at port 33434, increments
# Pros: Standard, reliable
# Cons: Blocked by some firewalls
                    </pre>
                </div>
                
                <div>
                    <h6>TCP TraceRoute (Bypass Firewalls):</h6>
                    <pre style="background: #f5f5f5; padding: 10px; border-radius: 5px;">
# Linux
traceroute -T google.com
traceroute -T -p 443 google.com  # HTTPS port

# Windows (third-party tools)
# Pros: Often works where ICMP/UDP blocked
# Cons: Requires special tools on Windows
                    </pre>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
        
        <div>
            <h5>Advanced Tools & Techniques</h5>
            
            <div style="background: white; padding: 15px; border-radius: 5px;">
                <h6>mtr (My TraceRoute) - Combined Tool:</h6>
                <pre style="background: #36454f; color: white; padding: 10px; border-radius: 5px;">
# Install: sudo apt install mtr (Linux)
# or brew install mtr (Mac)

# Basic usage
mtr google.com

# Options
mtr -r -c 10 google.com  # 10 reports, then exit
mtr -w google.com        # Wide report format
mtr -4 google.com        # Force IPv4
mtr -6 google.com        # Force IPv6

# Shows real-time packet loss and latency
                </pre>
                
                <div style="margin-top: 15px;">
                    <h6>pathping - Windows Advanced Tool:</h6>
                    <pre style="background: #36454f; color: white; padding: 10px; border-radius: 5px;">
# Windows only - combines ping and tracert
pathping google.com

# Takes longer but provides:
