<h3>Key Learning Points:</h3>
<ol>
    <li><b>LAN Design Principles:</b> Planning before implementation</li>
    <li><b>Physical Network Building:</b> Hands-on equipment setup</li>
    <li><b>Router Configuration:</b> Setting up gateway, DHCP, firewall</li>
    <li><b>Network Simulation:</b> Using tools like Packet Tracer</li>
    <li><b>Testing Methodology:</b> Systematic validation of network functionality</li>
    <li><b>Documentation:</b> Creating comprehensive network documentation</li>
    <li><b>Troubleshooting:</b> Solving common network setup issues</li>
</ol>

<div style="background-color: #e8f5e8; padding: 15px; margin: 20px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
    <h3>ğŸ’¡ LAN Building Best Practices:</h3>
    <ul>
        <li><b>Plan Thoroughly:</b> Measure twice, cut once applies to networking too</li>
        <li><b>Document Everything:</b> You'll forget details in 6 months</li>
        <li><b>Label Cables:</b> Use consistent labeling system at both ends</li>
        <li><b>Test Incrementally:</b> Test each connection as you make it</li>
        <li><b>Use Quality Equipment:</b> Don't cheap out on switches and cables</li>
        <li><b>Plan for Growth:</b> Leave 20-30% capacity for expansion</li>
        <li><b>Implement Security Early:</b> Easier to secure from start than retrofit</li>
        <li><b>Create Backup Configurations:</b> Backup router/switch configs regularly</li>
        <li><b>Consider Redundancy:</b> For critical networks, plan backup paths</li>
        <li><b>Train Users:</b> Document how to use the network properly</li>
    </ul>
</div>

