            "7-1": {
                "icon": "fa-server",
                "title": "Virtualization Fundamentals",
                "html": "<h1>Week 7, Day 1: Introduction to Virtualization</h1>\n<p>Today we explore virtualization concepts, learn why it's essential in modern IT, and compare popular virtualization platforms.</p>\n\n<div class=\"analogy-box\">\n    <b>Analogy: The Hotel vs. Apartment Building ğŸ¨ğŸ¢</b><br/>\n    - Physical Server = Apartment Building (one owner, one purpose)<br/>\n    - Virtualization = Hotel (multiple guests, isolated rooms)<br/>\n    - Hypervisor = Hotel Manager (allocates rooms, manages resources)<br/>\n    - Virtual Machine = Hotel Room (isolated, customizable, temporary)<br/>\n    - Snapshots = Room Photos (save state, restore if needed)<br/>\n</div>\n\n<h3>What is Virtualization?</h3>\n<p>Virtualization allows you to run multiple virtual machines (VMs) on a single physical machine, each with its own OS and applications.</p>\n\n<div style=\"background-color: #f0f8ff; padding: 20px; border-radius: 10px;\">\n<h4>ğŸ“Š Virtualization Types</h4>\n<table style=\"width:100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 15px 0;\">\n<tr style=\"background:#4A90E2; color:white;\">\n<th style=\"padding:10px; border:1px solid #ddd;\">Type</th>\n<th style=\"padding:10px; border:1px solid #ddd;\">Description</th>\n<th style=\"padding:10px; border:1px solid #ddd;\">Examples</th>\n</tr>\n<tr style=\"background:#f8f9fa;\">\n<td style=\"padding:8px; border:1px solid #ddd;\"><b>Full Virtualization</b></td>\n<td style=\"padding:8px; border:1px solid #ddd;\">Complete simulation of hardware, runs unmodified guest OS</td>\n<td style=\"padding:8px; border:1px solid #ddd;\">VMware, VirtualBox</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style=\"background:white;\">\n<td style=\"padding:8px; border:1px solid #ddd;\"><b>Para-virtualization</b></td>\n<td style=\"padding:8px; border:1px solid #ddd;\">Guest OS is aware it's virtualized, uses hypervisor APIs</td>\n<td style=\"padding:8px; border:1px solid #ddd;\">Xen, older VMware</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style=\"background:#f8f9fa;\">\n<td style=\"padding:8px; border:1px solid #ddd;\"><b>Containerization</b></td>\n<td style=\"padding:8px; border:1px solid #ddd;\">Shares host OS kernel, lightweight, fast startup</td>\n<td style=\"padding:8px; border:1px solid #ddd;\">Docker, Kubernetes</td>\n</tr>\n</table>\n</div>\n\n<h3>Hypervisor Types</h3>\n<div style=\"display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 20px;\">\n<div style=\"background:#e6f7ff; padding:15px; border-radius:8px;\">\n<h4>Type 1: Bare-Metal Hypervisor</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Runs directly on physical hardware</li>\n<li>Better performance & security</li>\n<li>Examples: VMware ESXi, Microsoft Hyper-V, KVM</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n<div style=\"background:#fff0e6; padding:15px; border-radius:8px;\">\n<h4>Type 2: Hosted Hypervisor</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Runs on top of a host OS</li>\n<li>Easier to set up, less overhead</li>\n<li>Examples: VirtualBox, VMware Workstation, Parallels</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n</div>\n\n<h3>Why Virtualize?</h3>\n<div style=\"background:#e8f5e8; padding:15px; border-radius:8px;\">\n<ul>\n<li><b>Cost Savings:</b> Reduce hardware, power, cooling costs</li>\n<li><b>Isolation:</b> One VM crash doesn't affect others</li>\n<li><b>Snapshot & Rollback:</b> Save VM state before updates</li>\n<li><b>Testing & Development:</b> Safe environment for experiments</li>\n<li><b>Disaster Recovery:</b> Quick migration of VMs to another host</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h3>Today's Lab: Install VirtualBox</h3>\n<div style=\"background:#f5f5f5; padding:15px; border-radius:8px;\">\n<ol>\n<li>Download VirtualBox from <a href='https://www.virtualbox.org' target='_blank'>virtualbox.org</a></li>\n<li>Install with default settings</li>\n<li>Download Ubuntu Server ISO from <a href='https://ubuntu.com/download/server' target='_blank'>ubuntu.com</a></li>\n<li>Create a new VM:\n<ul>\n<li>Name: Ubuntu-Server-Test</li>\n<li>Type: Linux</li>\n<li>Version: Ubuntu (64-bit)</li>\n<li>Memory: 2048 MB</li>\n<li>Create a virtual hard disk: 20 GB, VDI, dynamically allocated</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ol>\n</div>\n\n<h3>Homework</h3>\n<div style=\"background:#fff0e6; padding:15px; border-radius:8px;\">\n<p>Research and compare:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>VMware Workstation vs. VirtualBox vs. Hyper-V</li>\n<li>Create a table of features (snapshots, cloning, networking, performance)</li>\n<li>Identify which is best for: home lab, enterprise, developer use</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n"
            },
            "7-2": {
                "icon": "fa-cube",
                "title": "Creating Your First Virtual Machine",
                "html": "<h1>Week 7, Day 2: Lab - Create a Linux VM on Windows</h1>\n<p>Hands-on day! We'll install Ubuntu Server in VirtualBox and configure basic settings.</p>\n\n<div class=\"analogy-box\">\n    <b>Analogy: Building a House Inside a Warehouse ğŸ ğŸ­</b><br/>\n    - Warehouse = Your Physical Computer<br/>\n    - House Blueprint = ISO File (OS installer)<br/>\n    - Construction Crew = VirtualBox<br/>\n    - Finished House = Virtual Machine<br/>\n    - Furniture = Installed Applications<br/>\n</div>\n\n<h3>Step-by-Step VM Creation</h3>\n<div style=\"background:#f0f8ff; padding:20px; border-radius:10px;\">\n<h4>ğŸ“ Pre-Lab Checklist</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>âœ… VirtualBox installed (from Day 1)</li>\n<li>âœ… Ubuntu Server ISO downloaded (~2.5 GB)</li>\n<li>âœ… At least 20 GB free disk space</li>\n<li>âœ… 8 GB RAM recommended on host</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h3>Detailed Installation Walkthrough</h3>\n<div style=\"background:#f5f5f5; padding:15px; border-radius:8px;\">\n<h4>1. Create New VM</h4>\n<pre style='background:#e8e8e8; padding:10px; border-radius:5px;'>\nOpen VirtualBox â†’ Click \"New\"\nName: Ubuntu-Server-Lab\nType: Linux\nVersion: Ubuntu (64-bit)\nMemory: 2048 MB\nCreate virtual hard disk now â†’ VDI â†’ Dynamically allocated â†’ 20 GB\n</pre>\n\n<h4>2. Configure VM Settings</h4>\n<pre style='background:#e8e8e8; padding:10px; border-radius:5px;'>\nSelect VM â†’ Settings â†’ System:\n- Motherboard: Enable EFI (optional)\n- Processor: 2 CPUs\nSettings â†’ Display:\n- Video Memory: 128 MB\nSettings â†’ Storage:\n- Click Empty â†’ Choose Disk â†’ Select Ubuntu ISO\nSettings â†’ Network:\n- Attached to: NAT (for internet access)\n</pre>\n\n<h4>3. Install Ubuntu Server</h4>\n<pre style='background:#e8e8e8; padding:10px; border-radius:5px;'>\nStart VM â†’ Follow installer:\n1. Language: English\n2. Keyboard: US\n3. Network: DHCP (default)\n4. Proxy: Leave blank\n5. Mirror: Default\n6. Storage: Use entire disk\n7. Profile:\n   - Name: sysadmin\n   - Server name: ubuntu-server\n   - Username: admin\n   - Password: Choose secure one!\n8. SSH: Enable OpenSSH server (IMPORTANT for remote access)\n9. Additional software: Skip for now\n10. Reboot when done\n</pre>\n</div>\n\n<h3>Post-Installation Configuration</h3>\n<div style=\"display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 20px; margin-top:20px;\">\n<div style=\"background:#e6f7ff; padding:15px; border-radius:8px;\">\n<h4>Essential Commands to Run</h4>\n<pre style='background:#36454f; color:white; padding:10px; border-radius:5px;'>\n# Update system\nsudo apt update\nsudo apt upgrade -y\n\n# Install useful tools\nsudo apt install -y net-tools curl wget htop vim\n\n# Check IP address\nip a\nhostname -I\n\n# Test connectivity\nping -c 4 google.com\n</pre>\n</div>\n<div style=\"background:#fff0e6; padding:15px; border-radius:8px;\">\n<h4>VirtualBox Guest Additions (Optional)</h4>\n<p>Improves integration between host and guest:</p>\n<pre style='background:#36454f; color:white; padding:10px; border-radius:5px;'>\n# In VM menu: Devices â†’ Insert Guest Additions CD\n# Then in terminal:\nsudo mount /dev/cdrom /mnt\ncd /mnt\nsudo ./VBoxLinuxAdditions.run\nsudo reboot\n</pre>\n</div>\n</div>\n\n<h3>Troubleshooting Common Issues</h3>\n<div style=\"background:#ffe6e6; padding:15px; border-radius:8px;\">\n<table style=\"width:100%; border-collapse: collapse;\">\n<tr><th>Issue</th><th>Solution</th></tr>\n<tr><td>VM won't boot from ISO</td><td>Check Storage settings, ensure ISO is attached</td></tr>\n<tr><td>No internet in VM</td><td>Network â†’ Attached to: NAT or Bridged</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Screen resolution too small</td><td>Install Guest Additions</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Slow performance</td><td>Increase RAM/CPU, enable virtualization in BIOS</td></tr>\n</table>\n</div>\n\n<h3>Lab Challenge: Configure a Web Server in VM</h3>\n<div style=\"background:#f0f8ff; padding:15px; border-radius:8px;\">\n<p><b>Goal:</b> Install and run a basic web server inside your new VM</p>\n<pre style='background:#e8e8e8; padding:10px; border-radius:5px;'>\n# Install Apache\nsudo apt install apache2 -y\n\n# Start and enable Apache\nsudo systemctl start apache2\nsudo systemctl enable apache2\n\n# Create test page\necho '<h1>Hello from my first VM!</h1>' | sudo tee /var/www/html/index.html\n\n# Check if it's running\ncurl localhost\n</pre>\n<p><b>Advanced:</b> Try accessing it from your host browser using the VM's IP!</p>\n</div>\n"
            },
            "7-3": {
                "icon": "fa-camera",
                "title": "Snapshots, Cloning & Resource Management",
                "html": "<h1>Week 7, Day 3: Advanced VM Management</h1>\n<p>Today we master snapshots, cloning, and optimizing resource allocation for VMs.</p>\n\n<div class=\"analogy-box\">\n    <b>Analogy: Time Machine for Computers â±ï¸ğŸ’»</b><br/>\n    - Snapshot = Photo of your VM at a moment in time<br/>\n    - Clone = Identical twin of your VM<br/>\n    - Template = Blueprint for creating multiple VMs<br/>\n    - Linked Clone = VM that shares disk with parent (saves space)<br/>\n</div>\n\n<h3>Understanding Snapshots</h3>\n<div style=\"background:#f0f8ff; padding:20px; border-radius:10px;\">\n<h4>ğŸ“¸ What is a Snapshot?</h4>\n<p>A snapshot saves the <b>state</b> of a VM at a specific point in time, including:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Disk contents</li>\n<li>RAM (if saved)</li>\n<li>Settings</li>\n<li>Network configuration</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>When to Use Snapshots</h4>\n<table style=\"width:100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin:15px 0;\">\n<tr style=\"background:#4A90E2; color:white;\">\n<th style=\"padding:10px;\">Scenario</th>\n<th style=\"padding:10px;\">Snapshot Strategy</th>\n</tr>\n<tr><td>Before software installation</td><td>Take snapshot â†’ Install â†’ Rollback if fails</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Before system updates</td><td>Snapshot â†’ Update â†’ Test â†’ Keep or revert</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Testing configurations</td><td>Snapshot â†’ Change settings â†’ Compare</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Training environments</td><td>Clean snapshot for each student</td></tr>\n</table>\n</div>\n\n<h3>Hands-On: Working with Snapshots</h3>\n<div style=\"background:#f5f5f5; padding:15px; border-radius:8px;\">\n<h4>In VirtualBox GUI:</h4>\n<ol>\n<li>Shut down your Ubuntu VM</li>\n<li>Right-click VM â†’ Snapshots â†’ Take Snapshot</li>\n<li>Name: \"Clean-Install\"</li>\n<li>Description: \"Fresh Ubuntu with Apache installed\"</li>\n<li>Start VM â†’ Make changes (install new software)</li>\n<li>Shut down â†’ Right-click â†’ Restore Snapshot</li>\n</ol>\n\n<h4>Using VBoxManage (Command Line):</h4>\n<pre style='background:#36454f; color:white; padding:10px; border-radius:5px;'>\n# List VMs\nVBoxManage list vms\n\n# Take snapshot\nVBoxManage snapshot \"Ubuntu-Server-Lab\" take \"Pre-Update\" --description \"Before security updates\"\n\n# List snapshots\nVBoxManage snapshot \"Ubuntu-Server-Lab\" list\n\n# Restore snapshot\nVBoxManage snapshot \"Ubuntu-Server-Lab\" restore \"Clean-Install\"\n\n# Delete snapshot\nVBoxManage snapshot \"Ubuntu-Server-Lab\" delete \"Old-Snapshot\"\n</pre>\n</div>\n\n<h3>Cloning Virtual Machines</h3>\n<div style=\"display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 20px; margin-top:20px;\">\n<div style=\"background:#e6f7ff; padding:15px; border-radius:8px;\">\n<h4>Full Clone</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Complete copy of VM</li>\n<li>Takes more disk space</li>\n<li>Independent of original</li>\n<li>Good for: Production, archiving</li>\n</ul>\n<pre style='background:#e8e8e8; padding:10px; border-radius:5px;'>\n# In VirtualBox:\nRight-click VM â†’ Clone\nName: Ubuntu-Web-Server\nType: Full Clone\n</pre>\n</div>\n<div style=\"background:#fff0e6; padding:15px; border-radius:8px;\">\n<h4>Linked Clone</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Shares disk with parent</li>\n<li>Saves disk space</li>\n<li>Faster to create</li>\n<li>Good for: Testing, classrooms</li>\n</ul>\n<pre style='background:#e8e8e8; padding:10px; border-radius:5px;'>\n# In VirtualBox:\nRight-click VM â†’ Clone\nName: Ubuntu-Test-1\nType: Linked Clone\n</pre>\n</div>\n</div>\n\n<h3>Resource Allocation Best Practices</h3>\n<div style=\"background:#e8f5e8; padding:15px; border-radius:8px;\">\n<h4>CPU Allocation</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><b>Rule:</b> Don't allocate more vCPUs than physical cores</li>\n<li><b>Example:</b> 4-core CPU â†’ Max 3 vCPUs per VM (leave 1 for host)</li>\n<li><b>Tip:</b> Start with 1-2 vCPUs, monitor, increase if needed</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>Memory Allocation</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><b>Rule:</b> Leave at least 2 GB for host OS</li>\n<li><b>Formula:</b> Host RAM - 2 GB = Available for VMs</li>\n<li><b>Example:</b> 16 GB host â†’ 14 GB for VMs total</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>Disk Allocation</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><b>Dynamic:</b> Grows as needed, slower performance</li>\n<li><b>Fixed:</b> Full size allocated immediately, better performance</li>\n<li><b>SSD vs HDD:</b> VMs on SSD = 5-10x faster</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h3>Lab: Create a 3-VM Test Environment</h3>\n<div style=\"background:#f0f8ff; padding:15px; border-radius:8px;\">\n<p><b>Scenario:</b> Create a small network for testing</p>\n<ol>\n<li><b>Web Server VM:</b> Clone your Ubuntu VM, install Nginx</li>\n<li><b>Database VM:</b> New VM with Ubuntu, install MySQL</li>\n<li><b>Client VM:</b> Linked clone, test connectivity</li>\n</ol>\n\n<h4>Networking Configuration:</h4>\n<pre style='background:#e8e8e8; padding:10px; border-radius:5px;'>\nFor each VM â†’ Settings â†’ Network:\n- Web Server: Bridged (to act as real server)\n- Database: Internal Network (name: testnet)\n- Client: NAT (for internet) + Internal Network (testnet)\n</pre>\n\n<p><b>Test:</b> From Client VM, ping both Web Server and Database VMs</p>\n</div>\n\n<h3>Homework: Snapshot Strategy Document</h3>\n<div style=\"background:#fff0e6; padding:15px; border-radius:8px;\">\n<p>Create a snapshot strategy for a small business with:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>3 web servers</li>\n<li>2 database servers</li>\n<li>1 file server</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p><b>Include:</b></p>\n<ol>\n<li>Snapshot frequency (daily, weekly, before changes)</li>\n<li>Retention policy (keep 7 daily, 4 weekly, 12 monthly)</li>\n<li>Storage requirements calculation</li>\n<li>Recovery procedure</li>\n</ol>\n</div>\n"
            },
            "7-4": {
                "icon": "fa-globe",
                "title": "Real-World Virtualization Use Cases",
                "html": "<h1>Week 7, Day 4: Virtualization in Production</h1>\n<p>Today we explore how virtualization is used in real-world scenarios across different industries.</p>\n\n<div class=\"analogy-box\">\n    <b>Analogy: The Cloud Kitchen vs. Restaurant Chain ğŸ”ğŸ¢</b><br/>\n    - Physical Servers = Restaurant Kitchens<br/>\n    - Virtualization = Cloud Kitchen (multiple brands from one kitchen)<br/>\n    - VMs = Different food brands<br/>\n    - Load Balancer = Order routing system<br/>\n    - Auto-scaling = Adding chefs during rush hour<br/>\n</div>\n\n<h3>Enterprise Use Cases</h3>\n<div style=\"background:#f0f8ff; padding:20px; border-radius:10px;\">\n<h4>ğŸ¢ Server Consolidation</h4>\n<table style=\"width:100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin:15px 0;\">\n<tr style=\"background:#4A90E2; color:white;\">\n<th style=\"padding:10px;\">Before Virtualization</th>\n<th style=\"padding:10px;\">After Virtualization</th>\n<th style=\"padding:10px;\">Savings</th>\n</tr>\n<tr><td>20 physical servers</td><td>1 host with 20 VMs</td><td>95% less hardware</td></tr>\n<tr><td>80% power/cooling</td><td>20% power/cooling</td><td>75% reduction</td></tr>\n<tr><td>200 sq ft space</td><td>20 sq ft space</td><td>90% less space</td></tr>\n</table>\n\n<h4>ğŸ’° Cost Analysis Example</h4>\n<pre style='background:#e8e8e8; padding:10px; border-radius:5px;'>\nPhysical Server Costs (per server):\n- Hardware: $5,000\n- Power/Year: $500\n- Cooling/Year: $300\n- Space/Year: $200\n- Maintenance/Year: $1,000\nTotal/Server/Year: ~$7,000\n\nVirtual Server Costs (per VM):\n- Host Hardware: $20,000 (holds 20 VMs)\n- Power/Year: $2,000\n- VMware License: $5,000/year\nTotal/VM/Year: ~$1,850\n\nSAVINGS: 74% per server!\n</pre>\n</div>\n\n<h3>Development & Testing Environments</h3>\n<div style=\"display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 20px; margin-top:20px;\">\n<div style=\"background:#e6f7ff; padding:15px; border-radius:8px;\">\n<h4>ğŸš€ DevOps Pipeline</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><b>Developer:</b> Local VM with exact production environment</li>\n<li><b>Testing:</b> Automated tests run in isolated VMs</li>\n<li><b>Staging:</b> Clone of production for final testing</li>\n<li><b>Production:</b> Deploy tested VM image</li>\n</ul>\n<pre style='background:#36454f; color:white; padding:10px; border-radius:5px;'>\n# Example Vagrantfile for dev environment\nVagrant.configure(\"2\") do |config|\n  config.vm.box = \"ubuntu/focal64\"\n  config.vm.provision \"shell\", path: \"bootstrap.sh\"\n  config.vm.network \"private_network\", ip: \"192.168.33.10\"\n  config.vm.synced_folder \"./app\", \"/var/www/html\"\nend\n</pre>\n</div>\n<div style=\"background:#fff0e6; padding:15px; border-radius:8px;\">\n<h4>ğŸ§ª Software Testing Matrix</h4>\n<p>Test on multiple OS versions simultaneously:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Windows 10 + Windows 11</li>\n<li>Ubuntu 20.04 + 22.04</li>\n<li>CentOS 7 + CentOS Stream</li>\n<li>Different browser versions</li>\n</ul>\n<p><b>Benefit:</b> Catch OS-specific bugs before release</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n\n<h3>Disaster Recovery & Business Continuity</h3>\n<div style=\"background:#ffe6e6; padding:15px; border-radius:8px;\">\n<h4>ğŸ”¥ Disaster Recovery with Virtualization</h4>\n<table style=\"width:100%; border-collapse: collapse;\">\n<tr><th>Traditional DR</th><th>Virtualized DR</th><th>Improvement</th></tr>\n<tr><td>48+ hour recovery</td><td>15 minute recovery</td><td>99% faster</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Manual rebuild</td><td>VM restore from backup</td><td>Automated</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Different hardware</td><td>Hardware independent</td><td>No compatibility issues</td></tr>\n</table>\n\n<h4>Real Example: Hurricane Preparedness</h4>\n<pre style='background:#e8e8e8; padding:10px; border-radius:5px;'>\nMiami Hospital DR Plan:\n1. Primary Site: Miami datacenter\n2. Replicate VMs every 15 mins to Atlanta\n3. During hurricane warning:\n   - Increase replication to every 5 mins\n   - Test failover to Atlanta\n4. If Miami loses power:\n   - Automatically failover to Atlanta VMs\n   - Staff access via VPN\n5. After storm: Failback to Miami\n\nResult: Zero downtime during Category 4 hurricane\n</pre>\n</div>\n\n<h3>Cloud Computing & Virtualization</h3>\n<div style=\"background:#e8f5e8; padding:15px; border-radius:8px;\">\n<h4>â˜ï¸ IaaS (Infrastructure as a Service)</h4>\n<p>Cloud providers = Massive virtualization farms:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><b>AWS EC2:</b> Virtual servers in Amazon's cloud</li>\n<li><b>Azure VMs:</b> Microsoft's virtualization platform</li>\n<li><b>Google Compute Engine:</b> Google's VM offering</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>Virtualization vs Containerization</h4>\n<table style=\"width:100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin:15px 0;\">\n<tr style=\"background:#4A90E2; color:white;\">\n<th style=\"padding:10px;\">Aspect</th>\n<th style=\"padding:10px;\">Virtualization</th>\n<th style=\"padding:10px;\">Containerization (Docker)</th>\n</tr>\n<tr><td>Isolation</td><td>Full OS isolation</td><td>Process isolation</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Performance</td><td>Good</td><td>Excellent (near-native)</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Startup Time</td><td>30-60 seconds</td><td>1-2 seconds</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Disk Space</td><td>GBs per VM</td><td>MBs per container</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Use Case</td><td>Mixed OS, legacy apps</td><td>Microservices, cloud-native</td></tr>\n</table>\n</div>\n\n<h3>Case Study Analysis</h3>\n<div style=\"background:#f0f8ff; padding:15px; border-radius:8px;\">\n<h4>ğŸ“Š Netflix's Virtualization Strategy</h4>\n<p><b>Challenge:</b> Stream to 200M+ users globally</p>\n<p><b>Solution:</b> AWS + Massive virtualization</p>\n\n<h5>Architecture:</h5>\n<ol>\n<li><b>Encoding Farm:</b> Thousands of VMs converting videos</li>\n<li><b>Content Delivery:</b> VMs at edge locations worldwide</li>\n<li><b>Recommendation Engine:</b> Machine learning VMs</li>\n<li><b>Auto-scaling:</b> Add VMs during peak hours (evenings)</li>\n</ol>\n\n<p><b>Result:</b> 99.99% uptime, scales for \"Stranger Things\" releases</p>\n</div>\n\n<h3>Final Project: Virtualization Proposal</h3>\n<div style=\"background:#fff0e6; padding:15px; border-radius:8px;\">\n<p><b>Scenario:</b> Small accounting firm with:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>15 employees</li>\n<li>5 physical servers (file, email, database, web, backup)</li>\n<li>High electricity costs</li>\n<li>Slow disaster recovery</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p><b>Your Task:</b> Create a virtualization proposal including:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Recommended hardware (1-2 powerful servers)</li>\n<li>Virtualization platform (VMware, Hyper-V, or Proxmox)</li>\n<li>VM layout (which services go where)</li>\n<li>Cost analysis (hardware + software + savings)</li>\n<li>Disaster recovery plan</li>\n<li>Implementation timeline (6 months)</li>\n</ol>\n\n<p><b>Deliverable:</b> 3-5 page document or presentation</p>\n</div>\n\n<h3>Week 7 Key Takeaways</h3>\n<div style=\"background:#e8f5e8; padding:15px; border-radius:8px;\">\n<ul>\n<li><b>Virtualization</b> allows multiple VMs on one physical host</li>\n<li><b>Snapshots</b> provide rollback capability for safe testing</li>\n<li><b>Cloning</b> saves time deploying identical environments</li>\n<li><b>Resource allocation</b> requires careful planning</li>\n<li><b>Real-world benefits:</b> Cost savings, DR, scalability</li>\n<li><b>Cloud computing</b> = virtualization at massive scale</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n"
            },

            "8-1": {
                "icon": "fa-server",
                "title": "How Web Servers Work + HTTP/HTTPS Basics",
                "html": `<h1>Week 8, Day 1: How Web Servers Work + HTTP/HTTPS Basics</h1>
<p>Today we dive into web servers, understand how HTTP/HTTPS protocols work, and prepare for hands-on server setup in the coming days.</p>

<div class="analogy-box">
    <b>Analogy: The Digital Restaurant ğŸ½ï¸</b><br/>
    Web Server = Kitchen & Waitstaff<br/>
    Client (Browser) = Customer<br/>
    HTTP Request = Order placed<br/>
    HTTP Response = Meal served<br/>
    HTTPS = Private dining room (encrypted)<br/>
    Port = Table number<br/>
    DNS = Restaurant address book<br/>
</div>

<h3>How Web Servers Work: The Request-Response Cycle</h3>
<div style="background-color: #f0f8ff; padding: 20px; margin: 15px 0; border-radius: 10px;">
    <h4>ğŸŒ Web Server Architecture Diagram</h4>
    
