            "8-4": {
                icon: "fa-folder-open",
                title: "File Server Setup (Samba/FTP Basics)",
                html: `
    <h1>Week 8, Day 4: File Server Setup with Samba & FTP</h1>

    <p>
      Today we'll learn how to set up file servers for sharing files across networks using
      <b>Samba</b> (Windows-compatible file sharing) and <b>FTP</b> (cross-platform file transfer).
    </p>

    <div class="analogy-box">
      <b>Analogy: The School Library vs Book Delivery Service ğŸ“š</b><br/>
      <b>Samba</b> = School Library (browse, check out, return)<br/>
      <b>FTP</b> = Book Delivery Service (send and receive packages)<br/>
      <b>Shares</b> = Different book sections<br/>
      <b>Permissions</b> = Library card access levels<br/>
      <b>Users / Groups</b> = Students, Teachers, Staff<br/>
      <b>Mounting</b> = Adding the library to your personal space
    </div>

    <h3>Samba vs FTP: Comparison</h3>

    <div style="background-color:#f0f8ff;padding:20px;border-radius:10px;">
      <h4>ğŸ†š File Sharing Protocols Comparison</h4>

      <table style="width:100%;border-collapse:collapse;">
        <tr style="background:#4A90E2;color:white;">
          <th>Feature</th>
          <th>Samba (SMB/CIFS)</th>
          <th>FTP</th>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><b>Primary Use</b></td>
          <td>Network file sharing</td>
          <td>File transfers</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><b>Ports</b></td>
          <td>TCP 445</td>
          <td>TCP 21 / 20</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><b>Encryption</b></td>
          <td>SMB 3.0+</td>
          <td>FTPS / SFTP required</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><b>File Locking</b></td>
          <td>Yes</td>
          <td>No</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><b>Best For</b></td>
          <td>Shared folders & collaboration</td>
          <td>Bulk uploads & downloads</td>
        </tr>
      </table>
    </div>

    <h3>Part 1: Samba File Server Setup</h3>

    <div style="background:#fff0e6;padding:20px;border-radius:10px;">
      <h4>ğŸ§ Installing Samba (Ubuntu / Debian)</h4>

      <pre>
sudo apt update
sudo apt install samba samba-common-bin

sudo systemctl start smbd nmbd
sudo systemctl enable smbd nmbd
smbd --version
      </pre>

      <h4>âš™ï¸ Samba Configuration File</h4>

      <pre>
# /etc/samba/smb.conf
[global]
workgroup = WORKGROUP
server string = Classroom File Server
security = user
map to guest = bad user

[public]
path = /srv/samba/public
browseable = yes
read only = yes
guest ok = yes

[teachers]
path = /srv/samba/teachers
valid users = @teachers
writable = yes

[projects]
path = /srv/samba/projects
valid users = @teachers @students
writable = yes
      </pre>
    </div>

    <h3>Part 2: FTP Server Setup</h3>

    <div style="background:#e8f5e8;padding:20px;border-radius:10px;">
      <h4>ğŸ“¤ Installing vsftpd</h4>

      <pre>
sudo apt install vsftpd
sudo systemctl start vsftpd
sudo systemctl enable vsftpd
      </pre>

      <h4>ğŸ”§ Secure vsftpd Configuration</h4>

      <pre>
anonymous_enable=NO
local_enable=YES
write_enable=YES
chroot_local_user=YES
ssl_enable=YES
force_local_logins_ssl=YES
force_local_data_ssl=YES
      </pre>
    </div>

    <h3>Hands-On Lab</h3>

    <div style="background:#f0f8ff;padding:20px;border-radius:10px;">
      <b>Task:</b>
      <ol>
        <li>Set up Samba shares for teachers and students</li>
        <li>Create test files and verify permissions</li>
        <li>Set up FTP access and upload/download files</li>
        <li>Test access from another device</li>
      </ol>
    </div>

    <h3>Key Learning Points</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Differences between Samba and FTP</li>
      <li>User and group-based permissions</li>
      <li>Securing file servers</li>
      <li>Real-world classroom file sharing</li>
    </ul>

    <div style="background:#e0e0e0;padding:15px;border-radius:5px;">
      <h3>ğŸ’¡ Best Practices</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Use encryption (SMB3 / FTPS)</li>
        <li>Apply least-privilege permissions</li>
        <li>Monitor access logs</li>
        <li>Back up data regularly</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  `
            },

            "9-1": {
                "icon": "fa-shield-alt",
                "title": "Access Control Lists (ACLs) + Permissions",
                "html": `<h1>Week 9, Day 1: Access Control Lists (ACLs) & Permissions</h1>
<p>Today we dive deep into Linux/Windows permissions and Access Control Lists (ACLs) - the foundation of system security. You'll learn how to control exactly who can do what with files and directories.</p>

<div class="analogy-box">
    <b>Analogy: The High-Security Office Building ğŸ¢</b><br/>
    Files/Directories = Office rooms<br/>
    Users = Employees<br/>
    Groups = Departments (IT, HR, Sales)<br/>
    Permissions = Keycard access levels<br/>
    Owner = Office manager<br/>
    ACLs = Detailed access rules per person<br/>
    umask = Default keycard settings
</div>

<h3>Understanding Basic Linux Permissions</h3>
<div style="background-color: #f0f8ff; padding: 20px; margin: 15px 0; border-radius: 10px;">
    <h4>ğŸ“Š Linux Permission Structure</h4>
    
    <pre style="background: #f5f5f5; padding: 15px; border-radius: 8px;">
Example: drwxr-xr-x  2 alice teachers  4096 Jan 15 10:30 projects/

Breaking it down:
d rwx r-x r-x  |  alice teachers  |  4096  |  Jan 15 10:30  |  projects/
â”‚  â”‚   â”‚   â”‚       â”‚      â”‚           â”‚           â”‚              â”‚
â”‚  â”‚   â”‚   â”‚       â”‚      â”‚           â”‚           â”‚              â””â”€ File/Directory name
â”‚  â”‚   â”‚   â”‚       â”‚      â”‚           â”‚           â””â”€ Last modified timestamp
â”‚  â”‚   â”‚   â”‚       â”‚      â”‚           â””â”€ Size in bytes
â”‚  â”‚   â”‚   â”‚       â”‚      â””â”€ Group owner
â”‚  â”‚   â”‚   â”‚       â””â”€ User owner
â”‚  â”‚   â”‚   â”‚
â”‚  â”‚   â”‚   â””â”€ Permissions for Others (world)
â”‚  â”‚   â”‚       r = read, x = execute, - = no permission
â”‚  â”‚   â”‚
â”‚  â”‚   â””â”€ Permissions for Group
â”‚  â”‚       r = read, x = execute, - = no permission
â”‚  â”‚
â”‚  â””â”€ Permissions for Owner (User)
â”‚      r = read, w = write, x = execute
â”‚
â””â”€ File type: d = directory, - = regular file, l = symbolic link

Permission bits in detail:
r (read)    = 4 = Can view file contents/list directory
w (write)   = 2 = Can modify file/create files in directory
x (execute) = 1 = Can run file as program/enter directory
-           = 0 = No permission
    </pre>
    
    <h4>ğŸ”¢ Octal vs Symbolic Notation</h4>
    <table style="width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 15px 0;">
        <tr style="background: #4A90E2; color: white;">
            <th style="padding: 10px; text-align: left;">Symbolic</th>
            <th style="padding: 10px; text-align: left;">Octal</th>
            <th style="padding: 10px; text-align: left;">Meaning</th>
            <th style="padding: 10px; text-align: left;">Common Use</th>
        </tr>
        <tr style="background: #f8f9fa;">
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">rwx------</td>
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">700</td>
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Owner: rwx, Group: ---, Others: ---</td>
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Private user files</td>
        </tr>
        <tr style="background: white;">
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">rwxr-xr-x</td>
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">755</td>
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Owner: rwx, Group: r-x, Others: r-x</td>
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Programs, web files</td>
        </tr>
        <tr style="background: #f8f9fa;">
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">rwxr-x---</td>
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">750</td>
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Owner: rwx, Group: r-x, Others: ---</td>
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Team project directories</td>
        </tr>
        <tr style="background: white;">
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">rw-rw-r--</td>
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">664</td>
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Owner: rw-, Group: rw-, Others: r--</td>
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Shared documents</td>
        </tr>
        <tr style="background: #f8f9fa;">
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">rw-r--r--</td>
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">644</td>
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Owner: rw-, Group: r--, Others: r--</td>
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Web pages, config files</td>
        </tr>
        <tr style="background: white;">
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">rw-------</td>
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">600</td>
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Owner: rw-, Group: ---, Others: ---</td>
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Private data files</td>
        </tr>
    </table>
</div>

<h3>Special Permission Bits</h3>
<div style="background-color: #fff0e6; padding: 20px; margin: 15px 0; border-radius: 10px;">
    <h4>âš¡ Special Permission Flags</h4>
    
    <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr 1fr; gap: 20px; margin-top: 15px;">
        <div style="background: white; padding: 15px; border-radius: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">
            <h5>Set User ID (SUID)</h5>
            <p><b>Symbolic:</b> s or S in user execute position</p>
            <p><b>Octal:</b> 4xxx (e.g., 4755)</p>
            <p><b>Effect:</b> Program runs with owner's privileges</p>
            <p><b>Example:</b> <code>-rwsr-xr-x</code> on <code>/usr/bin/passwd</code></p>
            <pre style="background: #f5f5f5; padding: 10px; border-radius: 5px;">
# Set SUID
chmod u+s file
chmod 4755 file

# Find SUID files
find / -type f -perm /4000 2>/dev/null
            </pre>
        </div>
        <div style="background: white; padding: 15px; border-radius: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">
            <h5>Set Group ID (SGID)</h5>
            <p><b>Symbolic:</b> s or S in group execute position</p>
            <p><b>Octal:</b> 2xxx (e.g., 2755)</p>
            <p><b>Effect:</b> Files inherit directory's group</p>
            <p><b>Example:</b> <code>drwxr-sr-x</code> on shared directories</p>
            <pre style="background: #f5f5f5; padding: 10px; border-radius: 5px;">
# Set SGID on directory
chmod g+s directory
chmod 2775 directory

# Find SGID files
find / -type f -perm /2000 2>/dev/null
            </pre>
        </div>
        <div style="background: white; padding: 15px; border-radius: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">
            <h5>Sticky Bit</h5>
            <p><b>Symbolic:</b> t or T in others execute position</p>
            <p><b>Octal:</b> 1xxx (e.g., 1777)</p>
            <p><b>Effect:</b> Only owner can delete their files</p>
            <p><b>Example:</b> <code>drwxrwxrwt</code> on <code>/tmp</code></p>
            <pre style="background: #f5f5f5; padding: 10px; border-radius: 5px;">
# Set sticky bit
chmod +t directory
chmod 1777 directory

# Find sticky bit directories
find / -type d -perm /1000 2>/dev/null
            </pre>
        </div>
    </div>
    
    <h4>ğŸ§® Permission Calculation Examples</h4>
    <pre style="background: #36454f; color: white; padding: 15px; border-radius: 8px;">
# Calculate octal permissions:
# User: rwx = 4+2+1 = 7
# Group: r-x = 4+0+1 = 5
# Other: r-x = 4+0+1 = 5
# Result: 755

# With special bits:
# SUID (4) + User: rwx (7) + Group: r-x (5) + Other: r-x (5)
# 4 + 7 + 5 + 5 = 4755

# Common combinations:
chmod 755 file      # rwxr-xr-x (standard for executables)
chmod 644 file      # rw-r--r-- (standard for data files)
chmod 700 file      # rwx------ (private)
chmod 1777 dir      # drwxrwxrwt (world-writable with sticky)
chmod 2770 dir      # drwxrws--- (group collaboration)
chmod 4755 program  # -rwsr-xr-x (SUID program)
    </pre>
</div>

<h3>Access Control Lists (ACLs)</h3>
<div style="background-color: #e8f5e8; padding: 20px; margin: 15px 0; border-radius: 10px;">
    <h4>ğŸ¯ Why ACLs? Beyond Basic Permissions</h4>
    
    <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 20px; margin-top: 15px;">
        <div style="background: white; padding: 15px; border-radius: 8px;">
            <h5>Traditional Permissions Limitations</h5>
            <ul>
                <li>Only 3 sets: owner, group, others</li>
                <li>One group per file</li>
                <li>No per-user exceptions</li>
                <li>Limited flexibility</li>
                <li>Example: Can't give specific users different access</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
        <div style="background: white; padding: 15px; border-radius: 8px;">
            <h5>ACL Advantages</h5>
            <ul>
                <li>Multiple users with different permissions</li>
                <li>Multiple groups per file</li>
                <li>Default permissions for new files</li>
                <li>Mask for maximum allowed permissions</li>
                <li>Fine-grained control</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
    </div>
    
    <h4>ğŸ”§ ACL Commands and Syntax</h4>
    
    <pre style="background: #36454f; color: white; padding: 15px; border-radius: 8px;">
# Install ACL tools
sudo apt install acl        # Ubuntu/Debian
sudo yum install acl        # CentOS/RHEL

# Check if filesystem supports ACLs
tune2fs -l /dev/sda1 | grep acl
mount | grep acl

# Enable ACLs on filesystem (if needed)
sudo mount -o remount,acl /
# Or in /etc/fstab:
UUID=xxx / ext4 defaults,acl 0 1

# View ACLs
getfacl filename
getfacl -R directory/       # Recursive

# Set ACLs
setfacl -m u:username:permissions file
setfacl -m g:groupname:permissions file
setfacl -m o::permissions file        # Others
setfacl -m m::permissions file        # Mask

# Remove ACLs
setfacl -x u:username file           # Remove user entry
setfacl -x g:groupname file          # Remove group entry
setfacl -b file                      # Remove all ACLs

# Set default ACLs (for new files in directory)
setfacl -d -m u:username:permissions directory/
setfacl -d -m g:groupname:permissions directory/

# Examples:
setfacl -m u:bob:rwx project.txt
setfacl -m g:developers:rw- project.txt
setfacl -m u:alice:r-- project.txt
setfacl -m m::rwx project.txt        # Set mask
setfacl -d -m g:students:r-x classwork/
    </pre>
    
    <h4>ğŸ“‹ ACL Entry Types</h4>
    <table style="width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 15px 0;">
        <tr style="background: #27ae60; color: white;">
            <th style="padding: 8px;">Entry Type</th>
            <th style="padding: 8px;">Syntax</th>
            <th style="padding: 8px;">Example</th>
            <th style="padding: 8px;">Meaning</th>
        </tr>
        <tr style="background: #f8f9fa;">
            <td style="padding: 8px;">User</td>
            <td style="padding: 8px;"><code>user:name:perms</code></td>
            <td style="padding: 8px;"><code>user:bob:rwx</code></td>
            <td style="padding: 8px;">User-specific permissions</td>
        </tr>
        <tr style="background: white;">
            <td style="padding: 8px;">Group</td>
            <td style="padding: 8px;"><code>group:name:perms</code></td>
            <td style="padding: 8px;"><code>group:admins:rw-</code></td>
            <td style="padding: 8px;">Group-specific permissions</td>
        </tr>
        <tr style="background: #f8f9fa;">
            <td style="padding: 8px;">Other</td>
            <td style="padding: 8px;"><code>other::perms</code></td>
            <td style="padding: 8px;"><code>other::r--</code></td>
            <td style="padding: 8px;">Everyone else</td>
        </tr>
        <tr style="background: white;">
            <td style="padding: 8px;">Mask</td>
            <td style="padding: 8px;"><code>mask::perms</code></td>
            <td style="padding: 8px;"><code>mask::rwx</code></td>
            <td style="padding: 8px;">Maximum allowed permissions</td>
        </tr>
        <tr style="background: #f8f9fa;">
            <td style="padding: 8px;">Default User</td>
            <td style="padding: 8px;"><code>default:user:name:perms</code></td>
            <td style="padding: 8px;"><code>default:user:alice:rw-</code></td>
            <td style="padding: 8px;">Inherited for new files</td>
        </tr>
        <tr style="background: white;">
            <td style="padding: 8px;">Default Group</td>
            <td style="padding: 8px;"><code>default:group:name:perms</code></td>
            <td style="padding: 8px;"><code>default:group:staff:r-x</code></td>
            <td style="padding: 8px;">Inherited group permissions</td>
        </tr>
    </table>
</div>

<h3>Real-World ACL Examples</h3>
<div style="background-color: #e0e0e0; padding: 20px; margin: 15px 0; border-radius: 10px;">
    <h4>ğŸ¢ Classroom Scenario: Project Directory</h4>
    
    <pre style="background: #36454f; color: white; padding: 15px; border-radius: 8px;">
# Scenario: Class project with specific access requirements
# - Teacher (ms.jones): Full access
# - TAs (bob, alice): Read/write access  
# - Students group: Read/execute access
# - Specific student (charlie): Write access for peer review
# - Everyone else: No access

# Step 1: Create directory structure
sudo mkdir -p /srv/classroom/projects/final_project
sudo chown ms.jones:teachers /srv/classroom/projects/final_project
sudo chmod 750 /srv/classroom/projects/final_project

# Step 2: Set up groups
sudo groupadd students
sudo groupadd tas
sudo usermod -a -G students charlie
sudo usermod -a -G tas bob alice

# Step 3: Apply base permissions
cd /srv/classroom/projects/final_project

# Step 4: Add ACLs for specific access
setfacl -m u:ms.jones:rwx .                    # Teacher full access
setfacl -m g:tas:rwx .                         # TAs full access
setfacl -m g:students:r-x .                    # Students read/list
setfacl -m u:charlie:rwx .                     # Charlie extra access
setfacl -m m::rwx .                            # Set mask

# Step 5: Set default ACLs for new files
setfacl -d -m u:ms.jones:rwx .
setfacl -d -m g:tas:rwx .
setfacl -d -m g:students:r-x .
setfacl -d -m m::rwx .

# Step 6: Verify the setup
getfacl .

# Expected output:
# file: .
# owner: ms.jones
# group: teachers
# user::rwx
# user:ms.jones:rwx
# user:charlie:rwx
# group::r-x
# group:tas:rwx
# group:students:r-x
# mask::rwx
# other::---
# default:user::rwx
# default:user:ms.jones:rwx
# default:user:charlie:rwx
# default:group::r-x
# default:group:tas:rwx
# default:group:students:r-x
# default:mask::rwx
# default:other::---
    </pre>
    
    <h4>ğŸ” Practical ACL Commands</h4>
    <pre style="background: #f5f5f5; padding: 15px; border-radius: 8px;">
# Common ACL operations:

# 1. Grant specific user read access
setfacl -m u:guest:r-- important.doc

# 2. Allow group write access
setfacl -m g:editors:rw- document.txt

# 3. Remove a user's ACL entry
setfacl -x u:formeremployee file.txt

# 4. Copy ACL from one file to another
getfacl source.txt | setfacl --set-file=- dest.txt

# 5. Recursively apply ACL to directory
setfacl -R -m u:admin:rwX /shared/data/

# 6. View effective permissions
getfacl -e filename

# 7. Backup and restore ACLs
getfacl -R /important/dir > acl_backup.txt
setfacl --restore=acl_backup.txt

# 8. Set maximum permissions (mask)
setfacl -m m::rx script.sh  # No one can write, even owner

# 9. Check if file has ACLs
ls -l file.txt              # Shows '+' after permissions if ACLs exist

# 10. Remove all extended ACLs
setfacl -b directory/
    </pre>
</div>

<h3>Windows vs Linux Permissions</h3>
<div style="background-color: #fff0e6; padding: 20px; margin: 15px 0; border-radius: 10px;">
    <h4>ğŸªŸ Windows NTFS Permissions</h4>
    
    <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 20px; margin-top: 15px;">
        <div>
            <h5>Windows Permission Types</h5>
            <ul>
                <li><b>Full Control:</b> All permissions</li>
                <li><b>Modify:</b> Read, write, execute, delete</li>
                <li><b>Read & Execute:</b> Run programs, read files</li>
                <li><b>List Folder Contents:</b> View filenames</li>
                <li><b>Read:</b> View file contents</li>
                <li><b>Write:</b> Create/modify files</li>
                <li><b>Special Permissions:</b> Granular controls</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
        <div>
            <h5>Windows vs Linux Comparison</h5>
            <table style="width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse;">
                <tr style="background: #3498db; color: white;">
                    <th style="padding: 8px;">Linux</th>
                    <th style="padding: 8px;">Windows Equivalent</th>
                </tr>
                <tr style="background: #f8f9fa;">
                    <td style="padding: 8px;">chmod 755</td>
                    <td style="padding: 8px;">Read & Execute for Users, Read for Others</td>
                </tr>
                <tr style="background: white;">
                    <td style="padding: 8px;">chmod 644</td>
                    <td style="padding: 8px;">Read for Users, Read for Others</td>
                </tr>
                <tr style="background: #f8f9fa;">
                    <td style="padding: 8px;">chmod 700</td>
                    <td style="padding: 8px;">Full Control for Owner only</td>
                </tr>
                <tr style="background: white;">
                    <td style="padding: 8px;">SUID (4755)</td>
                    <td style="padding: 8px;">Run as Administrator</td>
                </tr>
                <tr style="background: #f8f9fa;">
                    <td style="padding: 8px;">SGID (2775)</td>
                    <td style="padding: 8px;">Creator Owner group inheritance</td>
                </tr>
            </table>
        </div>
    </div>
    
    <h4>ğŸ”€ Working with Windows Permissions from Linux</h4>
    <pre style="background: #36454f; color: white; padding: 15px; border-radius: 8px;">
# When mounting Windows shares in Linux:

# Mount with permissions preservation
sudo mount -t cifs //server/share /mnt/windows \
  -o username=user,password=pass,uid=1000,gid=1000,file_mode=0755,dir_mode=0755

# Common mount options for permissions:
# file_mode=0644     - Default file permissions
# dir_mode=0755      - Default directory permissions  
# uid=1000           - Set owner user ID
# gid=1000           - Set owner group ID
# nounix             - Disable Unix extensions
# noperm             - Ignore permission checks

# Samba configuration for Unix compatibility:
[global]
    unix extensions = yes
    map acl inherit = yes
    store dos attributes = yes

[share]
    force create mode = 0660
    force directory mode = 0770
    force user = smbuser
    force group = smbgroup
    inherit permissions = yes
    inherit acls = yes
