            "9-2": {
                "icon": "fa-user-tie",
                "title": "Admin vs. Guest Roles in Windows/Linux",
                "html": `<h1>Week 9, Day 2: Admin vs. Guest Roles in Windows & Linux</h1>
<p>Today we explore user role management, focusing on the critical distinction between administrator and standard user accounts in both Windows and Linux systems.</p>

<div class="analogy-box">
    <b>Analogy: Building Management vs Tenants ğŸ™ï¸</b><br/>
    <b>Administrator</b> = Building superintendent (master keys, system controls)<br/>
    <b>Standard User</b> = Apartment tenant (own space, limited building access)<br/>
    <b>Guest</b> = Visitor (temporary, restricted access)<br/>
    <b>Elevation</b> = Requesting superintendent help<br/>
    <b>Group Policy</b> = Building rules and regulations<br/>
    <b>UAC/sudo</b> = Access control gate
</div>

<h3>Understanding User Roles and Privileges</h3>
<div style="background-color: #f0f8ff; padding: 20px; margin: 15px 0; border-radius: 10px;">
    <h4>ğŸ‘¥ Role Hierarchy Comparison</h4>
    
    <table style="width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 15px 0;">
        <tr style="background: #4A90E2; color: white;">
            <th style="padding: 10px; text-align: left;">Role Level</th>
            <th style="padding: 10px; text-align: left;">Windows Equivalent</th>
            <th style="padding: 10px; text-align: left;">Linux Equivalent</th>
            <th style="padding: 10px; text-align: left;">Typical Privileges</th>
        </tr>
        <tr style="background: #f8f9fa;">
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;"><b>Super Administrator</b></td>
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Domain Admin, Enterprise Admin</td>
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">root (UID 0)</td>
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Unlimited system access</td>
        </tr>
        <tr style="background: white;">
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;"><b>Local Administrator</b></td>
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Local Administrators group</td>
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">sudo group, wheel group</td>
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Elevated privileges on local machine</td>
        </tr>
        <tr style="background: #f8f9fa;">
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;"><b>Power User</b></td>
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Power Users group (legacy)</td>
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Users with specific sudo rights</td>
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Limited administrative tasks</td>
        </tr>
        <tr style="background: white;">
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;"><b>Standard User</b></td>
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Users group</td>
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Regular user (UID â‰¥ 1000)</td>
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Own files, installed programs</td>
        </tr>
        <tr style="background: #f8f9fa;">
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;"><b>Guest</b></td>
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Guest account</td>
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">nobody, guest accounts</td>
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Minimal, temporary access</td>
        </tr>
        <tr style="background: white;">
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;"><b>Service Account</b></td>
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">NT AUTHORITY\SYSTEM</td>
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">System daemons (UID 1-999)</td>
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Specific service permissions</td>
        </tr>
    </table>
    
    <h4>ğŸ›¡ï¸ Security Philosophy: Least Privilege Principle</h4>
    <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 20px; margin-top: 15px;">
        <div style="background: #e3f2fd; padding: 15px; border-radius: 8px;">
            <h5>ğŸ”“ Traditional Approach (Insecure)</h5>
            <ul>
                <li>Everyone uses administrator accounts</li>
                <li>No separation of duties</li>
                <li>Malware gets full system access</li>
                <li>Accidental system changes are common</li>
                <li>Difficult to audit actions</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
        <div style="background: #e8f5e8; padding: 15px; border-radius: 8px;">
            <h5>ğŸ”’ Modern Approach (Secure)</h5>
            <ul>
                <li>Standard accounts for daily use</li>
                <li>Separate admin accounts for admin tasks</li>
                <li>Privilege elevation with approval</li>
                <li>Role-based access control</li>
                <li>Audit trails for all privileged actions</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
    </div>
</div>

<h3>Linux User & Group Management</h3>
<div style="background-color: #fff0e6; padding: 20px; margin: 15px 0; border-radius: 10px;">
    <h4>ğŸ§ Linux User Account Fundamentals</h4>
    
    <pre style="background: #f5f5f5; padding: 15px; border-radius: 8px;">
# Understanding /etc/passwd format
username:x:UID:GID:GECOS:homedir:shell

# Example entries:
root:x:0:0:root:/root:/bin/bash           # Superuser
daemon:x:1:1:daemon:/usr/sbin:/usr/sbin/nologin  # System account
nobody:x:65534:65534:nobody:/nonexistent:/usr/sbin/nologin  # Guest
alice:x:1000:1000:Alice Smith:/home/alice:/bin/bash  # Regular user
teacher:x:1001:1001:Class Teacher:/home/teacher:/bin/bash

# UID ranges:
# 0          = root (superuser)
# 1-99       = System accounts (daemons)
# 100-999    = System accounts for programs
# 1000-60000 = Regular users (configurable)
# 65534      = nobody (often used for guest access)

# Understanding /etc/group
groupname:x:GID:user1,user2,user3

# Example groups:
root:x:0:
sudo:x:27:alice,teacher
teachers:x:1001:teacher1,teacher2
students:x:1002:student1,student2,student3
    </pre>
    
    <h4>ğŸ”§ Linux User Management Commands</h4>
    
    <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 20px; margin-top: 15px;">
        <div>
            <h5>User Account Management</h5>
            <pre style="background: #36454f; color: white; padding: 15px; border-radius: 8px;">
# Create user with default settings
sudo useradd username
sudo useradd -m -s /bin/bash username  # With home directory and shell
sudo useradd -c "Full Name" username   # With comment/GECOS

# Set/change password
sudo passwd username
echo "password" | sudo chpasswd username  # Scriptable

# Modify existing user
sudo usermod -c "New Name" username      # Change comment
sudo usermod -s /bin/sh username         # Change shell
sudo usermod -L username                 # Lock account
sudo usermod -U username                 # Unlock account
sudo usermod -a -G groupname username    # Add to group
sudo usermod -d /new/home username       # Change home directory

# Delete user
sudo userdel username                    # Keep home directory
sudo userdel -r username                 # Remove home directory too

# View user information
id username                              # UID, GID, groups
finger username                          # Detailed info (if installed)
getent passwd username                   # Get passwd entry
chage -l username                        # Password aging info

# Switch users
su - username                            # Login as user (need password)
sudo -u username command                 # Run command as user
sudo -i -u username                      # Interactive shell as user
            </pre>
        </div>
        <div>
            <h5>Group Management</h5>
            <pre style="background: #36454f; color: white; padding: 15px; border-radius: 8px;">
# Create group
sudo groupadd groupname
sudo groupadd -g 1500 groupname         # With specific GID

# Modify group
sudo groupmod -n newname oldname        # Rename group
sudo groupmod -g 1600 groupname         # Change GID

# Delete group
sudo groupdel groupname

# Manage group members
sudo gpasswd -a username groupname      # Add user to group
sudo gpasswd -d username groupname      # Remove user from group
sudo gpasswd -A username groupname      # Make user group admin

# View group information
getent group groupname                  # Group entry
groups username                         # User's groups
id -Gn username                         # User's group names
id -G username                          # User's group IDs

# Primary vs supplementary groups
# Primary group: Default group for new files
# Supplementary groups: Additional group memberships
sudo usermod -g primarygroup username   # Change primary group
sudo usermod -a -G group1,group2 username  # Add supplementary groups

# Important system groups:
# sudo/wheel   - Can use sudo
# adm          - Can read log files
# disk         - Raw disk access
# video        - Video device access
# audio        - Audio device access
# plugdev      - Access external devices
            </pre>
