<h3>iptables - Linux Firewall</h3>
<div style="background-color: #e8f5e8; padding: 20px; margin: 15px 0; border-radius: 10px;">
    <h4>ğŸ§ iptables Fundamentals</h4>
    
    <pre style="background: #f5f5f5; padding: 15px; border-radius: 8px;">
# iptables Architecture
iptables â†’ Tables â†’ Chains â†’ Rules

Tables (from specific to general):
1. RAW      - Connection tracking exemption
2. MANGLE   - Packet modification (TTL, TOS)
3. NAT      - Network Address Translation
4. FILTER   - Packet filtering (main table)

Chains (for FILTER table):
â€¢ INPUT     - Incoming to local system
â€¢ OUTPUT    - Outgoing from local system
â€¢ FORWARD   - Through system (router)

# Basic iptables commands
iptables -L                    # List rules
iptables -L -n -v              # List with numbers and verbose
iptables -F                    # Flush all rules
iptables -X                    # Delete user-defined chains
iptables -Z                    # Zero packet counters
iptables -P INPUT DROP         # Set default policy
iptables -S                    # Show rules in script format

# Rule management
iptables -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 22 -j ACCEPT   # Append rule
iptables -I INPUT 1 -p icmp -j ACCEPT           # Insert at position 1
iptables -D INPUT -p tcp --dport 22 -j ACCEPT   # Delete rule
iptables -R INPUT 1 -p tcp --dport 80 -j ACCEPT # Replace rule

# Save and restore rules
iptables-save > /etc/iptables/rules.v4
iptables-restore < /etc/iptables/rules.v4
# Or use persistent package
apt install iptables-persistent
    </pre>
    
    <h4>ğŸ“ Practical iptables Examples</h4>
    
    <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 20px; margin-top: 15px;">
        <div>
            <h5>Basic Server Protection</h5>
            <pre style="background: #36454f; color: white; padding: 15px; border-radius: 8px;">
#!/bin/bash
# basic_server_firewall.sh

# Flush existing rules
iptables -F
iptables -X

# Set default policies
iptables -P INPUT DROP
iptables -P FORWARD DROP
iptables -P OUTPUT ACCEPT

# Allow loopback interface
iptables -A INPUT -i lo -j ACCEPT
iptables -A OUTPUT -o lo -j ACCEPT

# Allow established connections
iptables -A INPUT -m state --state ESTABLISHED,RELATED -j ACCEPT

# Allow ICMP (ping)
iptables -A INPUT -p icmp --icmp-type echo-request -j ACCEPT

# Allow SSH (port 22) from specific network
iptables -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 22 -s 192.168.1.0/24 -j ACCEPT

# Allow HTTP/HTTPS
iptables -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 80 -j ACCEPT
iptables -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 443 -j ACCEPT

# Allow DNS queries
iptables -A INPUT -p udp --dport 53 -j ACCEPT
iptables -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 53 -j ACCEPT

# Log dropped packets
iptables -A INPUT -j LOG --log-prefix "IPTABLES-DROP: "

# Save rules
iptables-save > /etc/iptables/rules.v4

echo "Firewall rules applied successfully!"
            </pre>
        </div>
        <div>
            <h5>Advanced Rules</h5>
            <pre style="background: #36454f; color: white; padding: 15px; border-radius: 8px;">
#!/bin/bash
# advanced_firewall.sh

# Rate limiting for SSH
iptables -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 22 -m state --state NEW \
    -m recent --set --name SSH
iptables -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 22 -m state --state NEW \
    -m recent --update --seconds 60 --hitcount 4 --name SSH -j DROP

# Port knocking (secret knock: 1000,2000,3000 then SSH)
iptables -N KNOCKING
iptables -N PASSED
iptables -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 1000 -j KNOCKING
iptables -A KNOCKING -p tcp --dport 1000 -m recent --set --name KNOCK1
iptables -A KNOCKING -p tcp --dport 2000 -m recent --rcheck --name KNOCK1 -j KNOCK2
iptables -A KNOCKING -p tcp --dport 3000 -m recent --rcheck --name KNOCK2 -j PASSED
iptables -A PASSED -p tcp --dport 22 -j ACCEPT

# Protection against SYN floods
iptables -A INPUT -p tcp --syn -m limit --limit 1/s --limit-burst 3 -j ACCEPT
iptables -A INPUT -p tcp --syn -j DROP

# Prevent port scanning
iptables -A INPUT -p tcp --tcp-flags ALL FIN,URG,PSH -j DROP
iptables -A INPUT -p tcp --tcp-flags ALL ALL -j DROP
iptables -A INPUT -p tcp --tcp-flags ALL NONE -j DROP

# Block specific countries (using ipset)
apt install ipset
ipset create blocked_countries hash:net
# Add country IP ranges to ipset...
iptables -A INPUT -m set --match-set blocked_countries src -j DROP

# Logging specific attacks
iptables -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 22 -m recent --update --seconds 60 \
    --hitcount 4 --name SSH -j LOG --log-prefix "SSH Brute Force: "
            </pre>
