                                <li>Configuration templates for different scenarios</li>
                                <li>Testing and validation procedures</li>
                                <li>Maintenance and update processes</li>
                            </ul>
                        </li>
                        <li><b>Policy Development Toolkit:</b>
                            <ul>
                                <li>Template Acceptable Use Policy</li>
                                <li>Stakeholder consultation guidelines</li>
                                <li>Legal compliance checklist</li>
                                <li>Communication plan for users</li>
                            </ul>
                        </li>
                        <li><b>Ethical Decision Framework:</b>
                            <ul>
                                <li>Flowchart for filtering decisions</li>
                                <li>Case studies with analysis</li>
                                <li>Conflict resolution procedures</li>
                                <li>Audit and review processes</li>
                            </ul>
                        </li>
                        <li><b>Educational Materials:</b>
                            <ul>
                                <li>User training modules</li>
                                <li>Parent/guardian information packets</li>
                                <li>Teacher/administrator guides</li>
                                <li>FAQ and troubleshooting resources</li>
                            </ul>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                    
                    <b>Deliverables:</b>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Complete framework document (20+ pages)</li>
                        <li>Technical configuration scripts and templates</li>
                        <li>Policy templates ready for customization</li>
                        <li>Presentation explaining the framework</li>
                        <li>Implementation case study for a specific organization</li>
                    </ul>
                    
                    <b>Bonus Challenges:</b>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Create a web-based filtering management portal</li>
                        <li>Develop AI-powered content categorization</li>
                        <li>Implement differential privacy in logging</li>
                        <li>Create gamified security awareness training</li>
                        <li>Develop an international compliance matrix</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <h3>Key Learning Points:</h3>
                <ol>
                    <li><b>Technical Methods:</b> Multiple approaches to content filtering (DNS, firewall, proxy)</li>
                    <li><b>Implementation Skills:</b> Hands-on configuration of filtering systems</li>
                    <li><b>Ethical Considerations:</b> Balancing security, privacy, and access rights</li>
                    <li><b>Policy Development:</b> Creating comprehensive and fair usage policies</li>
                    <li><b>Transparency:</b> Importance of clear communication about filtering</li>
                    <li><b>Legal Compliance:</b> Understanding relevant laws and regulations</li>
                </ol>

                <div style="background-color: #e0e0e0; padding: 15px; margin: 20px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
                    <h3>ğŸ’¡ Ethical Filtering Best Practices:</h3>
                    <ul>
                        <li><b>Be Transparent:</b> Clearly communicate what is blocked and why</li>
                        <li><b>Minimize Scope:</b> Only block what's necessary for the specific context</li>
                        <li><b>Provide Appeals:</b> Have a clear process for requesting access</li>
                        <li><b>Respect Privacy:</b> Collect only necessary data, protect what you collect</li>
                        <li><b>Regular Review:</b> Periodically reassess filtering rules and policies</li>
                        <li><b>Educate Users:</b> Teach why filtering exists, not just that it exists</li>
                        <li><b>Consider Context:</b> Different organizations need different approaches</li>
                        <li><b>Document Decisions:</b> Keep records of why filtering decisions were made</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                `
            },

            "11-1": {
                "icon": "fa-bug",
                "title": "Common System Errors & Blue Screen Analysis",
                "html": `<h1>Week 11, Day 1: Common System Errors & Blue Screen Analysis</h1>
                <p>Today weâ€™ll learn to identify and diagnose common system errors, especially Blue Screens of Death (BSOD), and master initial recovery methods.</p>

                <div class="analogy-box">
                    <b>Analogy: The System Doctorâ€™s Office ğŸ©º</b><br/>
                    System Errors = Physical Symptoms<br/>
                    Event Viewer = Medical Records<br/>
                    Blue Screen Codes = Diagnostic Report<br/>
                    Repair Tools = Treatment Methods<br/>
                    Backup = Health Insurance<br/>
                </div>

                <h3>Common System Error Categories</h3>
                <div style="background-color: #f0f8ff; padding: 20px; margin: 15px 0; border-radius: 10px;">
                    <h4>ğŸ“Š System Error Types Table</h4>
                    <table style="width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 15px 0;">
                        <tr style="background: #4A90E2; color: white;">
                            <th style="padding: 10px; text-align: left;">Error Type</th>
                            <th style="padding: 10px; text-align: left;">Common Symptoms</th>
                            <th style="padding: 10px; text-align: left;">Possible Causes</th>
                            <th style="padding: 10px; text-align: left;">First Response</th>
                        </tr>
                        <tr style="background: #f8f9fa;">
                            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Boot Failure</td>
                            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">No display, beep codes, stuck on BIOS screen</td>
                            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Failed HDD/SSD, corrupted bootloader, RAM issue</td>
                            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Check boot order, test RAM, use recovery media</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr style="background: white;">
                            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Blue Screen (BSOD)</td>
                            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Blue screen with error code, automatic restart</td>
                            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Driver conflict, hardware failure, memory corruption</td>
                            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Note error code, boot into Safe Mode, check Event Viewer</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr style="background: #f8f9fa;">
                            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Application Crash</td>
                            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">"App not responding", sudden closure, error popups</td>
                            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Missing DLLs, corrupted files, insufficient memory</td>
                            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Reinstall app, update software, check Task Manager</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr style="background: white;">
                            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Network Failure</td>
                            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">No internet, limited connectivity, DNS errors</td>
                            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Router issue, IP conflict, firewall block, driver problem</td>
                            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">ipconfig /release & /renew, restart router, disable firewall temporarily</td>
                        </tr>
                    </table>
                </div>

                <h3>Blue Screen of Death (BSOD) Deep Dive</h3>
                <div style="background-color: #fff0f0; padding: 20px; margin: 15px 0; border-radius: 10px;">
                    <h4>ğŸ›‘ BSOD Anatomy</h4>
                    <img src="https://i.dell.com/sites/csimages/App-Merchandizing_esupport_flatcontent_global_Images/all/bluescreen.png" alt="BSOD Example" style="width:100%; max-width:600px; border: 1px solid #ccc; margin: 10px 0;">
                    <p><b>Key Components:</b></p>
                    <ul>
                        <li><b>Error Name:</b> e.g., SYSTEM_THREAD_EXCEPTION_NOT_HANDLED</li>
                        <li><b>Stop Code:</b> e.g., 0x0000007B</li>
                        <li><b>Parameter Details:</b> Additional debug info</li>
                        <li><b>File/Driver Mentioned:</b> Often points to faulty driver</li>
                    </ul>

                    <h4>ğŸ” Common BSOD Stop Codes</h4>
                    <table style="width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 15px 0;">
                        <tr style="background: #d9534f; color: white;">
                            <th style="padding: 10px; text-align: left;">Stop Code</th>
                            <th style="padding: 10px; text-align: left;">Meaning</th>
                            <th style="padding: 10px; text-align: left;">Likely Cause</th>
                        </tr>
                        <tr style="background: #f8f9fa;">
                            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">0x0000007B</td>
                            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">INACCESSIBLE_BOOT_DEVICE</td>
                            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Boot drive not found or corrupted</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr style="background: white;">
                            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">0x000000D1</td>
                            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">DRIVER_IRQL_NOT_LESS_OR_EQUAL</td>
                            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Faulty driver or memory issue</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr style="background: #f8f9fa;">
                            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">0x00000050</td>
                            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">PAGE_FAULT_IN_NONPAGED_AREA</td>
                            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Bad RAM or driver memory corruption</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr style="background: white;">
                            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">0x000000124</td>
                            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">WHEA_UNCORRECTABLE_ERROR</td>
                            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Hardware failure (CPU, motherboard)</td>
                        </tr>
                    </table>
                </div>

                <h3>Hands-On: Diagnosing with Event Viewer & Reliability Monitor</h3>
                <div style="background-color: #e8f5e8; padding: 20px; margin: 15px 0; border-radius: 10px;">
                    <h4>ğŸ“ Using Event Viewer (Windows)</h4>
                    <p><b>Steps:</b></p>
                    <ol>
                        <li>Press <kbd>Win + R</kbd>, type <code>eventvwr.msc</code></li>
                        <li>Navigate to <b>Windows Logs â†’ System</b></li>
                        <li>Look for events with level <span style="color:red;">Error</span> or <span style="color:orange;">Warning</span></li>
                        <li>Note the Event ID and source</li>
                    </ol>
                    <pre style="background: #f5f5f5; padding: 15px; border-radius: 5px;">
                # Example Event IDs:
                # 41 â€” System rebooted without clean shutdown
                # 1001 â€” BSOD error report logged
                # 6008 â€” Unexpected shutdown
                # 7000 â€” Service failed to start
                    </pre>

                    <h4>ğŸ“ˆ Using Reliability Monitor</h4>
                    <p>Press <kbd>Win + R</kbd>, type <code>perfmon /rel</code></p>
                    <p>Shows a timeline of system stability, app crashes, and hardware failures.</p>
                </div>

                <h3>Practical Exercise: BSOD Simulation & Diagnosis</h3>
                <div style="background-color: #fff4e6; padding: 20px; margin: 15px 0; border-radius: 10px;">
                    <b>Task 1: Simulate a Boot Failure (Virtual Machine)</b>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Create a Windows VM in VirtualBox</li>
                        <li>Rename <code>ntoskrnl.exe</code> to cause a BSOD on boot</li>
                        <li>Boot into Windows Recovery Environment (WinRE)</li>
                        <li>Use <code>bootrec /rebuildbcd</code> to repair bootloader</li>
                    </ul>

                    <b>Task 2: Analyze a Minidump File</b>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Locate <code>C:\\Windows\\Minidump\\*.dmp</code></li>
                        <li>Download <b>WinDbg</b> or <b>BlueScreenView</b></li>
                        <li>Open dump file and identify faulty driver/module</li>
                        <li>Document findings in a troubleshooting report</li>
                    </ul>

                    <b>Task 3: Create a Bootable USB Repair Drive</b>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Use Windows Media Creation Tool or <code>rufus</code></li>
                        <li>Include system repair tools, antivirus scanner, and disk utilities</li>
                        <li>Test booting from USB and accessing recovery options</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <h3>Homework Assignment</h3>
                <div style="background-color: #f0f0ff; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
                    <b>Build a "System Error Diagnostics Toolkit"</b>
                    <p>Create a portable USB toolkit with:</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li><b>Bootable Linux Distro</b> (e.g., Ubuntu Live USB)</li>
                        <li><b>Windows Recovery Environment</b> (WinPE)</li>
                        <li><b>Diagnostic Tools:</b> MemTest86, CrystalDiskInfo, HWMonitor</li>
                        <li><b>Virus Scanner:</b> ClamAV or portable Malwarebytes</li>
                        <li><b>Password Reset Tool:</b> Offline NT Password & Registry Editor</li>
                        <li><b>Data Recovery Software:</b> TestDisk or Recuva Portable</li>
                    </ul>
                    <p><b>Deliverable:</b> Write a step-by-step guide on using each tool to diagnose and fix common system errors.</p>
                </div>

                <h3>Key Learning Points:</h3>
                <ol>
                    <li><b>BSOD Analysis:</b> Interpret stop codes and error messages</li>
                    <li><b>Event Viewer:</b> Use logs to trace system failures</li>
                    <li><b>Boot Process:</b> Understand and repair boot failures</li>
                    <li><b>Recovery Tools:</b> Use WinRE, Safe Mode, and repair commands</li>
                    <li><b>Diagnostic Methodology:</b> Systematic approach to troubleshooting</li>
                </ol>

                <div style="background-color: #e8f5e8; padding: 15px; margin: 20px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
                    <h3>ğŸ’¡ Troubleshooting Best Practices:</h3>
                    <ul>
                        <li><b>Stay Calm & Document:</b> Note error codes, symptoms, and recent changes</li>
                        <li><b>Isolate the Issue:</b> Hardware vs. software, recent updates, new installations</li>
                        <li><b>Use Safe Mode:</b> Boot with minimal drivers to rule out software conflicts</li>
                        <li><b>Check Connections:</b> Reseat RAM, cables, and peripherals</li>
                        <li><b>Update Drivers & BIOS:</b> But avoid updating during instability</li>
                        <li><b>Have a Backup:</b> Always ensure data is backed up before major repairs</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                `
            },
            "11-2": {
                "icon": "fa-hdd",
                "title": "Backup Strategies & The 3-2-1 Rule",
                "html": `<h1>Week 11, Day 2: Backup Strategies & The 3-2-1 Rule</h1>
                <p>Today weâ€™ll master backup fundamentals, implement the 3-2-1 rule, and create disaster recovery plans for real-world scenarios.</p>

                <div class="analogy-box">
                    <b>Analogy: The Data Fortress ğŸ°</b><br/>
                    Data = Treasure<br/>
                    Backup = Guard Towers<br/>
                    3-2-1 Rule = Layered Defense System<br/>
                    Recovery = Rebuilding After Attack<br/>
                    Redundancy = Multiple Escape Routes<br/>
                </div>

                <h3>Why Backups Matter: Real-World Scenarios</h3>
                <div style="background-color: #f0f8ff; padding: 20px; margin: 15px 0; border-radius: 10px;">
                    <h4>ğŸ“Š Common Data Loss Scenarios</h4>
                    <table style="width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 15px 0;">
                        <tr style="background: #4A90E2; color: white;">
                            <th style="padding: 10px; text-align: left;">Scenario</th>
                            <th style="padding: 10px; text-align: left;">Probability</th>
                            <th style="padding: 10px; text-align: left;">Impact</th>
                            <th style="padding: 10px; text-align: left;">Solution</th>
                        </tr>
                        <tr style="background: #f8f9fa;">
                            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Hardware Failure (HDD/SSD)</td>
                            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">High</td>
                            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Critical</td>
                            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Regular local backups + cloud sync</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr style="background: white;">
                            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Ransomware/Malware</td>
                            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Medium-High</td>
                            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Severe</td>
                            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Offline/immutable backups + versioning</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr style="background: #f8f9fa;">
                            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Accidental Deletion</td>
                            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Very High</td>
                            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Moderate</td>
                            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">File versioning + recycle bin policies</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr style="background: white;">
                            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Natural Disaster/Theft</td>
                            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Low</td>
                            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Catastrophic</td>
                            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Geographically separated backups</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr style="background: #f8f9fa;">
                            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Corrupted OS/Software</td>
                            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Medium</td>
                            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">High</td>
                            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">System image backups + rollback points</td>
                        </tr>
                    </table>
                </div>

                <h3>The 3-2-1 Backup Rule Explained</h3>
                <div style="background-color: #fff0f0; padding: 20px; margin: 15px 0; border-radius: 10px;">
                    <h4>ğŸ›¡ï¸ 3-2-1 Backup Strategy Visual</h4>
                    <div style="text-align: center; margin: 20px 0;">
                        <div style="display: inline-block; background: #e3f2fd; padding: 20px; border-radius: 10px; margin: 10px;">
                            <h3>3</h3>
                            <p><b>Copies of Data</b><br/>1 Primary + 2 Backups</p>
                        </div>
                        <div style="display: inline-block; background: #f3e5f5; padding: 20px; border-radius: 10px; margin: 10px;">
                            <h3>2</h3>
                            <p><b>Different Media</b><br/>HDD + Cloud or Tape</p>
                        </div>
                        <div style="display: inline-block; background: #e8f5e8; padding: 20px; border-radius: 10px; margin: 10px;">
                            <h3>1</h3>
                            <p><b>Offsite Copy</b><br/>Geographically separate</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <h4>ğŸ” 3-2-1 Implementation Examples</h4>
                    <table style="width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 15px 0;">
                        <tr style="background: #d9534f; color: white;">
                            <th style="padding: 10px; text-align: left;">User Type</th>
                            <th style="padding: 10px; text-align: left;">Implementation</th>
                            <th style="padding: 10px; text-align: left;">Tools/Cost</th>
                        </tr>
                        <tr style="background: #f8f9fa;">
                            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Home User</td>
                            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Primary: Computer â†’ Local Backup: External HDD â†’ Offsite: Google Drive/Backblaze</td>
                            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Free-$100/year</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr style="background: white;">
                            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Small Business</td>
                            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Primary: Server â†’ Local: NAS â†’ Offsite: AWS S3/Wasabi</td>
                            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">$500-$2000/year</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr style="background: #f8f9fa;">
                            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Enterprise</td>
                            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Primary: SAN â†’ Local: Tape Library â†’ Offsite: Colocation Facility</td>
                            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">$10,000+/year</td>
                        </tr>
                    </table>
                </div>

                <h3>Backup Types & Methods</h3>
                <div style="background-color: #e8f5e8; padding: 20px; margin: 15px 0; border-radius: 10px;">
                    <h4>ğŸ“ Backup Types Comparison</h4>
                    <table style="width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 15px 0;">
                        <tr style="background: #5cb85c; color: white;">
                            <th style="padding: 10px; text-align: left;">Type</th>
                            <th style="padding: 10px; text-align: left;">Description</th>
                            <th style="padding: 10px; text-align: left;">Pros</th>
                            <th style="padding: 10px; text-align: left;">Cons</th>
                        </tr>
                        <tr style="background: #f8f9fa;">
                            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;"><b>Full Backup</b></td>
                            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Copies all selected data every time</td>
                            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Fastest restore, complete data set</td>
                            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Slow, storage-intensive</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr style="background: white;">
                            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;"><b>Incremental</b></td>
                            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Only changes since last backup (any type)</td>
                            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Fast, storage-efficient</td>
                            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Slower restore (chain required)</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr style="background: #f8f9fa;">
                            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;"><b>Differential</b></td>
                            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Changes since last full backup</td>
                            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Faster restore than incremental</td>
                            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Storage grows over time</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr style="background: white;">
                            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;"><b>Mirror</b></td>
                            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Exact 1:1 copy, deletions sync</td>
                            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Simple, real-time</td>
                            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">No versioning, propagates deletions</td>
                        </tr>
                    </table>

                    <div style="margin-top: 20px; padding: 15px; background: #fff3cd; border-radius: 5px;">
                        <h5>ğŸ¯ Backup Strategy Example: GFS Rotation (Grandfather-Father-Son)</h5>
                        <ul>
                            <li><b>Daily (Son):</b> Incremental backups kept for 7 days</li>
                            <li><b>Weekly (Father):</b> Full backup on Sunday, kept for 4 weeks</li>
                            <li><b>Monthly (Grandfather):</b> Full backup on 1st of month, kept for 12 months</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <h3>Hands-On: Implementing Backup Solutions</h3>
                <div style="background-color: #fff4e6; padding: 20px; margin: 15px 0; border-radius: 10px;">
                    <b>Task 1: Windows Backup & Restore (Local)</b>
                    <ol>
                        <li>Open <code>Control Panel â†’ Backup and Restore (Windows 7)</code></li>
                        <li>Create a system image to external HDD</li>
                        <li>Schedule weekly full + daily incremental backups</li>
                        <li>Test restore: Boot from Windows Recovery USB and restore image</li>
                    </ol>

                    <b>Task 2: Linux rsync + cron (Command Line)</b>
                    <pre style="background: #f5f5f5; padding: 15px; border-radius: 5px;">
                # Create backup script
                #!/bin/bash
                BACKUP_DIR="/backup/$(date +%Y%m%d)"
                SOURCE_DIR="/home/user/important"
                LOG_FILE="/var/log/backup.log"

                mkdir -p $BACKUP_DIR
                rsync -avh --delete $SOURCE_DIR $BACKUP_DIR >> $LOG_FILE

                # Schedule with cron (daily at 2 AM)
                crontab -e
                # Add: 0 2 * * * /path/to/backup_script.sh
                    </pre>

                    <b>Task 3: Cloud Backup with rclone (Cross-Platform)</b>
                    <ol>
                        <li>Install rclone: <code>brew install rclone</code> (macOS) or <code>sudo apt install rclone</code> (Linux)</li>
                        <li>Configure Google Drive: <code>rclone config</code></li>
                        <li>Sync local folder to cloud:</li>
                        <pre style="background: #f5f5f5; padding: 10px; margin: 10px 0;">
                rclone sync /home/user/documents remote:backup/documents --progress
                        </pre>
                        <li>Setup bidirectional sync with versioning</li>
                    </ol>
                </div>

                <h3>Backup Verification & Testing</h3>
                <div style="background-color: #f0f0ff; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
                    <b>ğŸ” The Backup Test Checklist</b>
                    <ul>
                        <li><input type="checkbox"> Backup completes without errors</li>
                        <li><input type="checkbox"> Verify file count and size match source</li>
